<H2><A NAME=SECTION00061000000000000000>3.1 Hyperlinks in LaTeX</A></H2>
<P>
<A NAME=sechyper>&#160;</A> <A NAME=121>&#160;</A> <A NAME=122>&#160;</A> <A NAME=123>&#160;</A>
Arbitrary hypertext references are available 
through the commands 
<tt> htmladdnormallink</tt> and <tt> htmladdimg</tt>).
<P>
These are defined as follows:
<PRE>\htmladdnormallink{&lt;text&gt;}{&lt;URL&gt;}
\htmladdimg{&lt;URL&gt;}
</PRE>
The first command expects some text as the first argument and a URL as
the second argument. When processed by LaTeX (i.e. in the <tt> dvi </tt>
or <tt> ps</tt> output files), the URL will have no effect.
But when processed by the 
translator, 
<A HREF="http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/demoweb/url-primer.html">the URL will be used to provide
an active hypertext link</A> (to another
file, picture, sound file, movie, etc) e.g.
<PRE>\htmladdnormallink{&lt;URL&gt;}
	{http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/demoweb/url-primer.html}
</PRE>
<P>
A similar command called <tt> htmladdnormallinkfoot</tt> 
takes the same two arguments and has the same effect when generating
HTML as <tt> htmladdnormallink</tt>. But when processed by LaTeX it shows
the 
URL as a footnote.
<P>
In a similar way, the argument of the <tt> htmladdimg</tt> command 
should be a URL pointing
to an image. This URL is ignored in
the LaTeX hard copy output.
<P>
<BR> <HR>
<P><ADDRESS>
<I>Arndt Koester <BR>
Fri May 12 14:23:56 MESZ 1995</I>
