<TITLE>NCSA httpd ScriptAlias</TITLE>
<H1><IMG SRC="../icon.gif"> ScriptAlias directive</H1>

<HR>
<H2>Purpose</H2>

The ScriptAlias <A
HREF="../ConfigureInfo.html#Directive">directive</A> creates a virtual
directory on your server. Any accesses to that virtual directory will
be satisfied by returning the output of a <A
HREF="/cgi/">CGI server script</A> in that
directory. <P>

<HR>
<H2>Syntax</H2>

<CODE>ScriptAlias virtual path</CODE> <P>

<CODE>virtual</CODE> is the <A
HREF="../admin/AccessingFiles.html">translated location</A> of the
script directory. <P>

<CODE>path</CODE> is the full pathname of the directory which contains
server scripts which fulfill the request. <P>

Note: You should always place a trailing / after ScriptAlias
directives which reference directories, to prevent similar entries
from conflicting with each other. <P>

Several ScriptAlias directives may appear in the configuration file. <P>

<HR>
<H2>Example</H2>

<CODE>ScriptAlias /cgi-bin/ /usr/local/etc/httpd/cgi-bin/</CODE> <P>

This would cause requests such as <CODE>/cgi-bin/foo</CODE> to be satisfied
by running the script <CODE>/usr/local/etc/httpd/cgi-bin/foo</CODE>. <P>

Thus, if someone requested <CODE>/cgi-bin/a-script</CODE>, the server would
run <CODE>/usr/local/etc/httpd/cgi-bin/a-script</CODE> and send its output
to the client. <P>

<HR> <P>
<A HREF="Overview.html"><IMG SRC="../back.gif">Return to Resource
Configuration File Overview</A> <P>

<ADDRESS>httpd@ncsa.uiuc.edu</ADDRESS>
</DOC>
