<TITLE>NCSA httpd require</TITLE>
<H1><IMG SRC="../icon.gif"> require directive</H1>

<HR>
<H2>Purpose</H2>

The require directive affects which authenticated users can access a
given directory with a given method. <P>

<HR>
<H2>Scope</H2>

This directive is only available within <A HREF="Limit.html">Limit</A>
sections. <P>

<HR>

<H2>Syntax</H2>

<CODE>require entity en1 en2 ... enn</CODE> <P>

<CODE>en</CODE> are entity names, separated by spaces.  <P>

<CODE>entity</CODE> is one of the following: <P>

<UL>
<LI> <CODE>user</CODE> <P>

    Only the named <A HREF="../admin/UserManagement.html">users</A>
    can access this directory with the given methods. <P>

<LI> <CODE>group</CODE> <P>

    Only users in the named <A
    HREF="../admin/UserManagement.html#group">groups</A> can access this
    directory with the given methods. <P>

<LI> <CODE>valid-user</CODE> <P>

    All of the users defined in the <A
    HREF="AuthUserFile.html">AuthUserFile</A> are allowed access upon
    providing a valid password. <P>

</UL>

<HR>
<H2>Default</H2>

No default applies. <P>

<HR>

<H2>Example</H2>

<PRE>
&lt;Limit GET PUT&gt;
order deny,allow
deny from all
allow from .ncsa.uiuc.edu
require user ls
require group sdg
&lt;/Limit&gt;
</PRE>

In this directory, the server evaluates the deny directive
first. So, everyone is denied. It then evaluates the allow directive,
and decides to allow clients from .ncsa.uiuc.edu. Now, it uses user
authentication and only allows users who are named ls or are in the
group sdg.<P>

<HR> <P>

<A HREF="Overview.html#Directives"><IMG SRC="../back.gif">Return to access
configuration overview</A> <P>

<ADDRESS>httpd@ncsa.uiuc.edu</ADDRESS>
</DOC>
<DOC>
