<TITLE>NCSA httpd Scripts</TITLE>
<H1><IMG SRC="../icon.gif"> Writing Scripts</H1>

Writing scripts for NCSA httpd should not be a problem. You can write
them in C, PERL, /bin/sh, or ANYTHING that will produce a UNIX
executable program. <P>
<HR> <P>

There are two major ways of accessing a script. Listed are the methods
(for use with the <A HREF="../access/Limit.html">Limit</A> directive),
and their uses. <P>

<UL>
<LI> GET <P>
<UL>
<LI> Widely supported
<LI> Responds to <A
     HREF="http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/General/Internet/WWW/HTMLPrimer.html">HTML</A> &lt;ISINDEX&gt; documents
<LI> Limited response to HTML <A HREF="http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/SDG/Software/Mosaic/Docs/fill-out-forms/overview.html">forms</A>
</UL>
 <P>
<LI> POST <P>
<UL>
<LI> Fully responds to any size HTML form. <P>
</UL>
</UL>

<HR> <P>

We recommend you start with <A HREF="script-data/GetScripts.html">writing GET
scripts</A>, and if you're interested, read about <A
HREF="script-data/PostScripts.html">writing POST scripts</A>. <P>

<HR> <P>

<A HREF="Overview.html"><IMG SRC="../back.gif">Return to
administration overview</A> <P>

<ADDRESS>httpd@ncsa.uiuc.edu</ADDRESS>
</DOC>
