<HR>
<font size=2>| <a href="#headlines">Latest Headlines</a> | <a href="#other">Other Top Stories</a> | <a href="#features">NC4 Features</a> |</font><br>
<br>
<A NAME="headlines"><font size=+3><b>Bay Area Headlines</b></font></A> <br>
<i>Updated:
<!------------Do not type before this line --------------->
<!----- Update Time and date---->
1/21/97 11am
<!---------------------------------------------->
<br>
</i></font>
<br>
</center>
<table>
<tr>
<td valign=top>
<!--- Picture for story 1 -->
<IMG SRC="images/icons/bay_bridge.gif" WIDTH="72" HEIGHT="54" BORDER="0" hspace=10>
<!---------------------------------------------->
</td><td valign=top>
<b>
<!------------ Begin Headline 1------------------>
Bay Bridge Review
<!---------------------------------------------->
</B><BR>
<!------------ Begin Story 1 --------------------->
California highway officials are reviewing engineering 
information for an eventual recommendation on whether to fix or replace 
the east span of the San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge. Secretary Dean 
Dunphy of the Business, Transportation and Housing Agency has favored 
retrofitting the span. But Senator Quentin Kopp of San Francisco says 
evidence indicates that replacing it would be cheaper. A final 
recommendation is expected by February. 

<!---------------------------------------------->
<P>
</td></tr><tr><td valign=top>
<!--- Picture for story 2 -->
<IMG SRC="images/icons/policecar.gif" WIDTH="72" HEIGHT="54" BORDER="0" hspace=10>
<!---------------------------------------------->
</td><td valign=top>
<b>
<!------------ Begin Headline 2 ------------------>
SF Police Custody Death
<!---------------------------------------------->
</B><BR>
<!------------ Begin Story 2 --------------------->
The San Francisco police commission meets tomorrow to consider charges against five police officers. A suspect died while in their custody. The officers are accused of failing to provide prompt medical 
help for Aaron Williams after pepper spraying him. They also allegedly lied to investigators. Williams, a burglary suspect, died in June 1995 in back of a police van. The San Francisco medical examiner said Williams died of "excited delirium" caused by acute cocaine poisoning. But he suffered 18 injuries during the arrest struggle. 

<!---------------------------------------------->
<P>
</td></tr><tr><td valign=top>
<!--- Picture for story 3 -->
<IMG SRC="images/icons/eagle.gif" WIDTH="72" HEIGHT="54" BORDER="0" hspace=10>
<!---------------------------------------------->
</td><td valign=top>
<b>
<!------------ Begin Headline 3 ------------------>
Parts of Yosemite to Re-open
<!---------------------------------------------->
</B><BR>
<!------------ Begin Story 3 -- ------------------>
Parts of Yosemite National Park, closed because of flooding and damage from a series of New 
Year's storms, are scheduled to reopen Wednesday, park officials 
said. 
   The Wawona area and some wilderness sections of the park in the 
higher portions of the park will open then. Like Yosemite Valley, 
they have been closed since Jan. 1. 
   Yosemite Valley and other parts of the scenic park, will remain 
closed because of flood and storm damage. 
<p><b>Higher Park Fee Delayed...</b>  The park's new $20 seven-day pass fee, 
which was to have started Jan. 15, will be reduced temporarily to the old 
charge of $5 
because of limited services, said park spokesman Kendell Thompson. 
   Services in Wawona that will reopen include the Wawona 
Campground, the Wawona Store, the Chevron service station, Pine 
Tree Market and the Wawona post office. The Wawona Hotel and 
Restaurant will remain closed. 

<!---------------------------------------------->
<p></td></tr>
</table>
<br clear=left>
<hr>
<br>
<center>
<A NAME="other"><font size=+3><b>Other Top Stories</b></font></A>
</center>
<br>
<BR>
<UL>
<LI><B>
<!------------ Begin Headline 4 ------------------>
Street-Side Birth
<!---------------------------------------------->
</B><BR>
<!------------ Begin Story 4 --------------------->
A woman gave birth on a San Francisco street 
and just kept on walking. 
   A witness saw yesterday's unusual delivery and cradled the 
newborn in a blanket until an ambulance arrived. 
   Police Lieutenant Tim Foley says the mother thought she had a 
miscarriage and tried walking to a hospital. 
   The baby was three months premature. 


<!---------------------------------------------->
<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>
<!------------ Begin Headline 5 ------------------>
SF Bay Selenium Suit
<!---------------------------------------------->
</B><BR>
<!------------ Begin Story 5 --------------------->
The Supreme Court is refusing to protect Union 
Oil from a clean-water lawsuit over selenium in San Francisco Bay. 
   The justices today left intact rulings that let environmental 
groups press their claims against Unocal in federal court. This, 
despite a prior settlement between the oil company and a state 
regulatory board. 
   Unocal has a state permit to discharge wastewater from its Rodeo 
refinery that contains selenium, a toxic substance found in crude 
oil. 

<!---------------------------------------------->
<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>
<!------------ Begin Headline 6 ------------------>
Flood Donations
<!---------------------------------------------->
</B><BR>
<!------------ Begin Story 6 --------------------->
acific Bell and Arco have joined the list of 
companies donating money and services to help flood victims. The 
phone company is giving 250 thousand dollars in grants for 
emergency assistance, temporary housing, food vouchers and home 
repairs. 
   The company is also donating 5 thousand dollars worth of prepaid 
calling cards for use by the Salvation Army. 
   Arco will donate 100 thousand dollars to aid flood victims in 
California and Nevada. Butte County's chapter of the American Red 
Cross will receive 5 thousand dollars, and Yuba and Sutter Counties 
get 15 thousand. 

<!---------------------------------------------->
<BR>
<BR>
<LI><B>
<!------------ Begin Headline 7 ------------------>
Simpson Closing Arguments Today
<!---------------------------------------------->
</B><BR>
<!------------ Begin Story 7 --------------------->
Closing arguments are set to get under way shortly in O.J. 
Simpson's civil trial. The judge and lawyers met this morning to 
clear up issues related to jury instructions. 
  Deliberations probably will begin Thursday after the judge 
instructs jurors on the law. If jurors decide to slap Simpson with 
punitive damages, a brief hearing will be held to explore the state 
of Simpson's finances, followed by another round of deliberations. 
   Legal analysts said the summations will likely be a combination 
of style and substance. 

<!---------------------------------------------->
