<blockquote>
<H2>BASEBALL'S FLOOD DIES</H2>
<!---------------------------->
Former St. Louis Cardinals centerfielder Curt Flood, whose challenge of baseball's reserve clause paved the way for the free agency era, died Monday at the age of 59 after a long battle with throat cancer. A three-time All-Star and seven-time Gold Glove winner, Flood batted over .300 six times, including a career best .335 in 1967, and led the National League in hits with 211 in 1964, leading the Cardinals to a pair of World Series titles. But free agency remains his legacy. Following the 1969 season, Flood refused to report after being dealt to the Philadelphia Phillies and sued major league baseball, saying the reserve clause, by which players were bound to their teams and prevented from playing for the teams of their choice, violated anti-trust law. Flood sat out the 1970 season while taking his fight to the Supreme Court. And though the Court ruled against him in 1972, three years later an arbitrator did grant free agency to pitchers Dave McNally and Andy Messersmith. <P> The Sharks opened the second half of their season on the business end of a 6-1 thumping at the hands of the Vancouver Canucks in Vancouver. Markus Nasland scored twice, Pavel Bure and Martin Gelinas each added a goal and an assist for the Canucks who converted on three of their seven power play opportunities. Ulf Dahlen the lone goal for the Sharks. San Jose now home to host the Los Angeles Kings on Wednesday. They drop the puck at 7:30pm at the San Jose Arena. <P> The NFL coaching carousel made a sudden stop in St. Louis where the Rams have called a Tuesday press conference at which time they are expected to name Dick Vermeil, out of coaching since 1982, their new head coach replacing the fired Rich Brooks. Vermeil took the Philadelphia Eagles to their lone Super Bowl, losing to the Raiders in 1981, and compiled a 57-51 record in seven seasons in Philadelphia. Since his retirement, Vermeil has worked as a college football analyst for ABC. <P> The Atlanta Falcons officially named Dan Reeves their new head coach and vice-president of football operations, replacing June Jones who was dismissed last month. The 53-year old Reeves, took the Denver Broncos to three Super Bowls in 12 years before going 31-33 in four seasons with the New York Giants. His 149 wins, the most among active coaches and rank 10th all-time. <P> And published reports out of Boston say Sunday's Super Bowl will be Bill Parcells' last game as head coach of the Patriots. The Boston Globe reporting Parcells will step down to take over control of the New York Jets. Neither Parcells nor the team had any comment. <P> And 49ers quarterbacks coach Matt Cavanaugh is reportedly the Chicago Bears top choice to become their new offensive co-ordinator. The only stumbling block apparently a possible promotion to the same position in San Francisco, though that seems unlikely since new head coach Steve Mariucci is expected to handle the bulk of the play-calling next season. <P> Chicago Bulls forward Dennis Rodman has reportedly agreed to pay camerman Eugene Amos, whom Rodman kicked in the groin
during a game in Minnesota last Wednesday $200,000. Rodman is currently in the midst of an 11-game suspension which will cost him more than $1 million in salary. <P> College ball, Stanford slipped two places to number 17 in the latest Associated Press college basketball poll. Kansas remains number one with Clemson up a notch to number two and Kentucky up two to number 3. Wake Forest falls two to number four and Utah jumps from 9th to round out the top five. Cal received five votes and would be 43rd if you cared to take things that far. <P> On the distaff side, Stanford remains 3rd, behind Connecticut and Old Dominion. USF would be 30th. <P> The Warriors back from a 3-3 road trip Tuesday night to host the Dallas Mavericks. A 7:30pm tip at the San Jose Arena. <P> Anke Huber and Carlos Moya became the Australian Open's first semi-finalists. The 12th seeded Huber taking out Kimberly Po 6-4, 6-1 in just 66 minutes to reach the semis for the 2nd consecutive year. While the unseeded Moya excused number 14 Felix 
Mantilla in four sets to reach his first Grand Slam semi-final in just his fifth attempt. <P> And finally, San Jose Clash forward Eric Wynalda has been named the US Soccer's player of the year, becoming the first two-time recipient of the award. Wynalda received 79 first place votes, easily outdistancing runner-up Casey Keller. 
<!---------------------------->
</blockquote>
