<!-----------------------Begin Page Title ---------------------------> 



<TITLE> HMO Advocate</TITLE>



<!------------------------------------------------------------------>



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif" LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973"

ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom>



<br><br>



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150  height=1>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<blockquote>



<font size=+3><b>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title --------------------------->



HMO Advocate



<!------------------------------------------------------------------>



</b></font><br>



<font size=2><i>



<!-- Enter date aired -->



Aired: January 17, 1997



<!-------------------->



</i></font><p>



<!-----------------------Begin Story --------------------------->



<IMG SRC="hmoadv_images/1.jpeg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120" WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



<b>You or someone in your family is sick. You want a specialist or a certain test or procedure, but your HMO says no.

In this age of managed care and HMOs, what clout does the individual health consumer have? Contact4 Consumer Reporter

Emerald Yeh has the story of one man whose mission is to help sick, and often frightened, people get what they

need.</b><p>



Steve and Sondra Legallet hit a roadblock with their medical plan last year when it was discovered their baby would

need surgery. Their son, Sean, was born with a giant mole covering the back of his head and neck. Left alone, it

could develop into a deadly cancer. The dispute was not over the need for surgery, it was over who would do it.<p>



<IMG SRC="hmoadv_images/2.jpeg" ALIGN=right HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120" WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



"We felt we wanted a doctor who had done this exact procedure on an infant and a pediatric anesthesiologist," says

Steve Legallet.<p>



"Research said that the pediatric anesthesiologist was very, very important to the surgery process," says Sondra

Legallet. "We wanted to find someone who had a lot of experience doing that."<p>



The clinic turned down the Legallet's request for the outside specialists, saying its own plastic surgeon was

qualified enough. "The medical group - the HMO'S - seemed so much larger than us," says Steve. "And the appeals

process seems complicated. It seemed to us if we go "no" a repeated number of times, we were basically kind of

stuck."<p>



<IMG SRC="hmoadv_images/3.jpeg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120" WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



Instead, the Legallets found help through a medical consumer advocate named Dr. Vincent Riccardi. Not only is he a

doctor, but Riccardi has worked for HMO's, reviewing physician's requests for tests and specialists for their

patients. <p>



It's Dr. Riccardi's belief that consumers need insider's knowledge like his in going up against a powerful health

care industry. His first advice to the Legallets was NOT to file an appeal with their HMO, but to try to get their

own doctor to help them get the specialists they need.<p>



"The point is don't make it into a grievance because if it's made into a grievance, it sort of falls out of the realm

of the doctor's handle," advises Dr. Riccardi. "He can say, 'I'm sorry. I can't handle it. It's in the grievance

process.'" <p>



<IMG SRC="hmoadv_images/4.jpeg" ALIGN=right HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120" WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



Through Dr. Riccardi's coaching and guidance over the phone, the Legallets got their son to UCSF where a pediatric

surgeon and pediatric anesthesiologist handled Sean's operation.<p>



Sean came through the surgery beautifully. Dr. Riccardi's help spanned a six-month period. For his services, the

Legallets were charged $50.<p>



"He really helped steer us through the whole process and made it a lot less intimidating," says Sondra.<p> 



"I believe somebody who's been in the system, who knows it inside and out -- an educator, a coach, an advocate and

all those different roles -- can make a tremendous difference with somebody who's unfamiliar to the system," adds

Steve.<p>



<b>Dr. Vincent Riccardi works out of his home in La Crescenta in Los Angeles County. If you'd like to reach him, you

can call the 1-800 directory assistance and ask for American Medical Consumers.</b><p>



<!------------------------------------------------------------------>



</BLOCKQUOTE>



</td>



</tr>



