<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->



<TITLE> Corneal Ring Implant</TITLE>



<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif" LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 



<br><br>



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150 height=1>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<blockquote>



<font size=+3><b>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title --------------------------->



Corneal Ring Implant



<!-----------------------End Story Title --------------------------->



</b></font><br>



<font size=2><i>



Aired: 



<!-- Enter date aired -->



January 17, 1997



<!-------------------->



</i></font><p>



<!-----------------------Begin text --------------------------->



<IMG SRC="corneal_images/1.jpeg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120" WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



<b>For millions of Americans who are nearsighted, glasses or contact lenses are a way of life. Many would gladly dump them if they could. Now doctors at UC San Francisco are testing a new surgical technique that could give people better vision without permanently altering their eyes.</b><p>



Diane Milbur says she is lost without her glasses, "Without glasses you wouldn't want me driving for sure." But now she is about to try a new procedure that she hopes will let her throw away her glasses forever -- a corneal ring implant. <p>



<IMG SRC="corneal_images/2.jpeg" ALIGN=right HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120" WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



Here's how it works: In myopia or short-sightedness, the eye focuses light in front of rather than on the retina, and that causes blurry vision. With corneal ring implants, surgeons implant two tiny semi-circles of plastic on the surface of the eye that reshapes the cornea, thus correcting the problem. <p>



UCSF professor of ophthalmology Dr. Richard Abbott says the procedure has one big advantage over other eye surgeries, "We can take the ring segments out in a very simple procedure and the refractive error, or the power of their eye, will return to the original state. So that is certainly one advantage; that this procedure is reversible." <p>



<IMG SRC="corneal_images/3.jpeg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120" WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



The procedure requires only a topical anesthetic and takes about half an hour. Studies show about a 95 percent success rate in restoring people's vision to at least 20-40 -- that's the level you need to pass a DMV test. <p>



Recovery is quick. Roger Riley had corneal rings implanted on a Monday, "Wednesday I went back to school during the day. Thursday, I was back at school and Thursday night I was back driving the taxi, which is how I earn my living. That's how quick it was." <p>



<b>Right now the procedure is only being tested on people with moderate myopia. If you'd like to find out if you qualify for corneal ring implants, call (415) 476-5021.</b><p>



<!------------------------------------------------->



</BLOCKQUOTE></td>



</tr>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<a href="../home.html"><img src="../../images/back.gif" width=82 height=36 border=0 vspace=2></a><br>



</td>



<td valign=top><center><a href="../../home.html"><img src="../../images/nc4_header_sm.gif" border=0 width=156 height=39></a><br><br>



