<HTML>



<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->



<TITLE> Potty Training</TITLE>



<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif" LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 



<br><br>



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150 height=1>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<blockquote>



<font size=+3><b>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title --------------------------->



Potty Training



<!-----------------------End Story Title --------------------------->



</b></font><br>



<font size=2><i>



Aired: 



<!-- Enter date aired -->



January 14, 1997



<!-------------------->



</i></font><p>



<!-----------------------Begin text --------------------------->



<b>A new study has reassuring news for parents struggling to toilet train their infants. The study says you're not alone. More and more American children are getting toilet trained at later ages than a few decades ago. But experts say it's not cause for concern.</b><p>



The new study says when it comes to toilet training toddlers, more and more parents are taking a relaxed approach these days. Annette Hayes says she is letting her daughter, Janette, set her own pace, "I let her go round with no diapers on, and let her use the potty when she could get up and do it. And there's basically no pressure; don't want to make a big deal out of it. It worked really well." <p>



In the 1960's, most children were fully toilet trained by about 27 months. This latest study, in the journal Pediatrics, found that now only 22 percent are trained by age two and a half, 60 percent by age three, and 88 percent by age three and a half. <p>

   

California Pacific Medical Center's Dr. George Lee, a pediatrician, says part of the reason may be changing attitudes among parents. "I think one of the things that has happened is that parents have become older by the time they have children, and so are more concerned with working with the child, to supporting the child, to having a relationship with the child, and not having this dominant parental 

authority where you will do it because 'I say so.'"<p>



The study, the largest of its kind in thirty years, shows that most kids know what the toilet is but that many just don't want to use it -- at least not until they are ready. <p>



Till then, experts say the best advice is let the child set their own pace. Give them encouragement, not discouragement. "You don't force a child," advises Dr. Lee. "You don't approach a child with negative connotations or punishment or demean the child in the process or their age or their manner in which they are trying to learn." <p>



<b>One interesting side note: Girls tend to toilet train themselves faster than boys, though no one is quite sure why that is the case.</b><p>



<!------------------------------------------------->



</BLOCKQUOTE></td>



</tr>



