<HTML>



<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->



<TITLE> Seldane</TITLE>



<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif" LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 



<br><br>



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150 height=1>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<blockquote>



<font size=+3><b>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title --------------------------->



Seldane



<!-----------------------End Story Title --------------------------->



</b></font><br>



<font size=2><i>



Aired: 



<!-- Enter date aired -->



January 13, 1997



<!-------------------->



</i></font><p>



<!-----------------------Begin text --------------------------->



<b>The FDA today proposed pulling seldane, one of the most popular allergy drugs, off the market. The reason is because of potentially deadly side effects.</b><p>



When it was introduced in 1985, seldane became a godsend for millions of allergy sufferers. It was the first antihistamine to relieve the sneezing, watery eyes and runny nose of allergies without causing drowsiness. <p>



But in 1992, doctors discovered seldane could cause potentially fatal heart problems for some people. Those at risk were people taking the anti-fungal drug ketaconazole or the antibiotic erythromycin and anyone with liver disease. <p>



That led the FDA to issue a black box warning. Laura Polonsky, a drug information specialist at Alta Bates Hospital in Berkeley, explains, "Basically what this says to the pharmacist and physicians and other practitioners is to be particularly careful about giving this particular medication, and to make sure they follow the black box warning." <p>



The FDA is in essence saying that warning is not enough, and recommends pulling the drug from the market altogether. The drug's manufacturer, Hoechst Marion Roussel, plans to fight that decision; saying the drug is safe and effective. <p>

   

NewsCenter4's Healthbeat team allergist, Dr. Michael Lenoir, says even if seldane is withdrawn from the market, people with allergies won't suffer because there are new and equally effective drugs to take its place. "I think seldane was a very popular drug," says Dr. Lenoir. "...People are very wedded to that kind of drug. But I think in view of the fact that there are other drugs just as effective, I think most patients can make the shift without losing any decrease in symptoms." <p>



<b>The FDA recommends that anyone on seldane right now should talk to their doctor about switching to another, safer drug.</b><p>



<!------------------------------------------------->



</BLOCKQUOTE></td>



</tr>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<a href="../home.html"><img src="../../images/back.gif" width=82 height=36 border=0 vspace=2></a><br>



</td>



<td valign=top><center><a href="../../home.html"><img src="../../images/nc4_header_sm.gif" border=0 width=156 height=39></a><br><br>



