<HTML>



<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->



<TITLE> Women & Cigars</TITLE>



<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif" LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 



<br><br>



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150 height=1>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<blockquote>



<font size=+3><b>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title --------------------------->



Women & Cigars



<!-----------------------End Story Title --------------------------->



</b></font><br>



<font size=2><i>



Aired: 



<!-- Enter date aired -->



January 10, 1997



<!-------------------->



</i></font><p>



<!-----------------------Begin text --------------------------->



<b>While breast cancer kills more than forty thousand people every year, lung

cancer is an even bigger killer of women. That's why a new trend has health

experts worried. More and more women are starting to smoke cigars, and experts

say cigars carry serious health risks for even occasional smokers.</b><p>



<IMG SRC="cigars_images/1.jpeg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120"

WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



Cigar smoking among women is on the rise. Sales of premium cigars rose 33 percent

last year alone; many attribute a large part of that to women. One reason is that

powerful advertising is giving it a glamorous image.<p>



"It feels sexy. It feels kind of like you're in control," remarks Nick Zeidan,

owner of San Francisco's California Tobacco Center. He says business is booming,

"Everything is going great. It's hard to keep up with demand."<p>



<IMG SRC="cigars_images/2.jpeg" ALIGN=right HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120"

WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



But while cigars have a glamorous image, the reality is very different. The 1982

Surgeon General's report found that women who smoke cigars regularly triple their

chance of lung cancer. Cigars also increase the risk of lip and mouth cancer from

four to ten times. They also boost the risk of kidney, bladder, and liver cancer

and heart disease. Another problem with cigars is second-hand smoke; it's more

toxic than cigarette smoke.<p>



Dr. Ray Weisberg is on the board of the American Cancer Society, "I think many of

the people who have taken it [cigar-smoking] up as a socially-smart thing to do

don't appreciate what kinds of risks they are putting themselves at. And I wonder

if they are non-smokers, in terms of cigarettes, if they appreciate that they are

doing the same thing with cigars that they would be doing if they were cigarette

smokers."<p>



<IMG SRC="cigars_images/3.jpeg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120"

WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



Health experts are now trying to counter the image put out by the tobacco

industry and increase awareness about the dangers of smoking. San Francisco's

tobacco free project gets its message across by using ads comparing cigars to dog

droppings: "Cigars. They look like what they smell like. Don't put them in your

mouth."<p>



<b>Health experts want to make people aware that even an occasional smoker gets a

concentrated exposure to the cancer-causing chemicals in cigars. And they point

out there's nothing glamorous about lip cancer.</b><p>



<!------------------------------------------------->



</BLOCKQUOTE></td>



</tr>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<a href="../home.html"><img src="../../images/back.gif" width=82 height=36 border=0 vspace=2></a><br>



</td>



<td valign=top><center><a href="../../home.html"><img src="../../images/nc4_header_sm.gif" border=0 width=156 height=39></a><br><br>



