<HTML>



<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->



<TITLE>Grapes & Cancer</TITLE>



<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif"

LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom>



<br><br>



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150 height=1>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<blockquote>



<font size=+3><b>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title --------------------------->



Grapes & Cancer



<!-----------------------End Story Title --------------------------->



</b></font><br>



<font size=2><i>



Aired:



<!-- Enter date aired -->



January 9, 1997



<!-------------------->



</i></font><p>



<!-----------------------Begin text --------------------------->



<b>There's new evidence that red wine might have distinct health benefits.

Studies have already shown that red wine may help reduce the risk of heart

disease. Now a new study says something in grapes may also help fight

cancer.</b><p>



This latest study shows that a substance in grapes, called resveratrol, prevents

skin and breast cancer in mice. "And in addition to that - since it is a natural

product - we think it's not very toxic," says Dr. John Pezzuto of the University

of Illinois, "so it's a very exciting lead in terms of cancer-chemo

prevention."<p>



The study in the journal "Science" says resveratrol blocks cancer while it is

still developing before a tumor appears. <p>



"It makes more sense to try and block these steps and prevent the tumor, rather

than waiting till you see a tumor and trying to treat it with...fairly expensive

and inefficient methods," says Dr. Pezzuto. <p>



The best sources of resveratrol are grapes and grape products such as grape juice

and jam. Smaller, but appreciable, amounts are found in red wine. But to get the

same amount the mice consumed you would have to drink five gallons of wine a day.

<p>



"Obviously [drinking five gallons of wine] isn't applicable, so one has to think

about dietary supplements or alternative sources of the compound," adds Dr.

Pezzuto. <p>



Those could be years away. So in the meantime, researchers say stick with the

basics. <p>



"It looks like those people who consume high levels of fruit and vegetables

compared to those who don't consume that much, if you compare the two groups we

can lower our cancer rate by 50 percent," says dietitian Phyllis Bowen. <p>



<b>The researchers are already testing resveratrol to see if can prevent prostate

cancer in rats. If those experiments prove successful, the next stage could be

testing in humans. But that may be some years away.</b><p>



<!------------------------------------------------->



</BLOCKQUOTE></td>



</tr>



