<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->



<TITLE> Drunk Driving</TITLE>



<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif" LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 



<br><br>



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150 height=1>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<blockquote>



<font size=+3><b>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title --------------------------->



Drunk Driving



<!-----------------------End Story Title --------------------------->



</b></font><br>



<font size=2><i>



Aired: 



<!-- Enter date aired -->



January 7, 1997



<!-------------------->



</i></font><p>



<!-----------------------Begin text --------------------------->



<b>Nationally, every 32 minutes someone dies from an alcohol-related traffic accident. That's more than 17,000 people each year. Despite efforts at encouraging people not to drink and drive, a new survey shows alcohol remains a constant companion on the highway.</b><p>



Each year one and a half million people are arrested for driving while intoxicated. Yet a new national survey reveals the number of times people admit they've driven after having too much to drink is more than 80 times higher than the number of arrests. <p>



"We're talking about 123 million episodes of alcohol-impaired driving in the United States," says Dr. Robert Brewer of the Centers For Disease Control and Prevention. "That's a huge number of episodes; it's approximately one episode of alcohol-impaired driving every four seconds." <p>



The researchers from the Centers For Disease Control and Prevention say the most sobering finding in their report, which can be found in the Journal of the American Medical Association, is that ten million of the DUI episodes were by drivers aged 18 to 20 -- who are not legally allowed to drink. <p>



"We need to lower the legal blood alcohol level for drivers under age 21 to .02," says Dr. Brewer. "That is, enact zero tolerance laws. Underage drivers should not be consuming any alcoholic beverages  prior to driving."<p>



The survey revealed drinking patterns greatly influenced whether someone reported driving while impaired. People who consume two or more drinks every day were most likely to report episodes of alcohol-impaired driving. <p>



"There tends to be a misconception that some people have that there is, in fact, some safe level 

of drinking before driving," adds Dr. Brewer. "In fact, there is no safe level of drinking before operating a motor vehicle and our findings indicate that though there are still a number of people who believe that alcohol-impaired driving is OK." <p>



<b>An even more sobering thought: The study did not include anyone under 18 and relied on people to respond honestly about the number of times they drove while drunk. So it's likely the real number of drunk driving episodes is even higher.</b><p>



<!------------------------------------------------->



</BLOCKQUOTE></td>



</tr>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<a href="../home.html"><img src="../../images/back.gif" width=82 height=36 border=0 vspace=2></a><br>



</td>



<td valign=top><center><a href="../../home.html"><img src="../../images/nc4_header_sm.gif" border=0 width=156 height=39></a><br><br>



<hr>



<font size=2>Copyright &copy; 1996 <a href="http://www.kron.com"><b>KRON-TV</b></a>. All rights reserved.</font>



