<HTML>



<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->



<TITLE> Latex Allergy</TITLE>



<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif" LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 



<br><br>



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150 height=1>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<blockquote>



<font size=+3><b>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title --------------------------->



Latex Allergy



<!-----------------------End Story Title --------------------------->



</b></font><br>



<font size=2><i>



Aired: 



<!-- Enter date aired -->



December 18, 1996



<!-------------------->



</i></font><p>



<!-----------------------Begin text --------------------------->



<b>One of the most common materials used in health care these days is latex. It's used in everything from gloves to bandages and blood pressure cuffs. But while it's meant to help protect people, latex also poses a hidden and potentially deadly threat for millions of Americans.</b><p>



For most health care workers latex gloves are the first line of defense against infection. But for Greta Ten Bruggencate, latex almost cost her life. <p>



As a nurse Greta worked with latex everyday. It caused some mild skin rashes, but nothing serious -- or so she thought. Then one day she collapsed and went into anaphylactic shock. <p>



"Luckily a Santa Clara Fire District truck was passing the area closely by and they had a paramedic on board and he intubated me, brought on the lung machine, started an IV drip, and virtually saved my life," she recalls. <p>



While Greta's case is extreme, it is not isolated. A recent study found that around six percent of the population has some kind of latex allergy. Among health care workers who are most exposed to latex, the number is between eight and twelve percent. <p>



Dr. Peter Maguire is an allergy specialist at Lucille Packard Children's Hospital at Stanford. He says attacks can be triggered not only by exposure to latex, but also by a cross-reaction from eating certain fruits such as bananas, chestnuts, kiwis, and avocado. "So," says Dr. Maguire, "people who have latex allergy and eat those fruits have shown up in doctors offices and emergency rooms very sick with allergic symptoms." <p>



Greta's attack was triggered by eating a nectarine. Now she says she is afraid to even go to the store, "I walk up and down the aisles thinking, 'what is latex' and 'am I going to breathe in something and fall on the floor here and have my throat close. And will the emergency teams get to me in time?' It's very frightening." <p>



<b>There is no cure. Often the only outward sign people are allergic is a rash when wearing latex gloves. The problem has gotten so bad the FDA is considering warnings on all medical products containing latex.</b><p>



<!------------------------------------------------->



</BLOCKQUOTE></td>



</tr>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<a href="../home.html"><img src="../../images/back.gif" width=82 height=36 border=0 vspace=2></a><br>



</td>



<td valign=top><center><a href="../../home.html"><img src="../../images/nc4_header_sm.gif" border=0 width=156 height=39></a><br><br>



<hr>



<font size=2>Copyright &copy; 1996 <a href="http://www.kron.com"><b>KRON-TV</b></a>. All rights reserved.</font>



</center>



</td>



</tr>



