<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->



<TITLE> Getty Anniversary</TITLE>



<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif" LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973"

ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 



<br><br>



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150 height=1>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<blockquote>



<font size=+3><b>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title --------------------------->



Getty Anniversary



<!-----------------------End Story Title --------------------------->



</b></font><br>



<font size=2><i>



Aired: 



<!-- Enter date aired -->



December 13, 1996



<!-------------------->



</i></font><p>



<!-----------------------Begin text --------------------------->



<b>One year ago tomorrow AIDS activist Jeff Getty took part in an experimental procedure that was both risky and

controversial. He underwent a transplant of bone marrow from a baboon. We wanted to check in with Getty and see how

he's doing one year after making medical history. Healthbeat reporter Pam Moore has his story.</b><p>



This time last year, Jeff Getty was in a hospital room undergoing radiation and chemotherapy to suppress his immune

system in preparation for a baboon bone marrow transplant. <p>



<IMG SRC="getty_images/1.jpeg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120" WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



Today, it's a very different story. Says Getty, "I weigh about 15 or 20 pounds more. I'm not chronically sick

anymore, I'm fairly well. I'm enjoying life to the fullest again and making long-term plans." <p>



The idea behind the transplant was simple: baboons do not get AIDS. Doctors hoped by transplanting baboon bone marrow

into Getty, they would also transplant some AIDS-resistant stem cells. In effect, giving him a new immune system. <p>



That does not appear to have happened. Tests show the baboon cells stayed in Getty's system for just two weeks after

the procedure; not long enough to have an impact. <p>



"I think it was a very bold experiment that clearly failed," remarks Dr. Warner Greene, who heads the Gladstone

Institute of Virology and Immunology. He says while the experiment failed to engraft baboon bone marrow into Getty,

it did raise interesting questions, "It had a wonderful spin-off in that...we did something to him that made him a

lot better." <p>



<IMG SRC="getty_images/2.jpeg" ALIGN=right HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120" WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



Getty thinks he's better because the treatment he underwent to suppress his immune system for the transplant actually

killed the cells where HIV was growing. "My guess right now is I benefited from the chemotherapy and the radiation,"

he says. "I can pretty much recall back to the days when I got that therapy. I can remember that I really started

feeling good." <p>



The procedure was controversial from the start. It upset animal rights activists who protested the killing of a

baboon for human research. Some scientists also feared that a cross-species transplant could 

introduce animal diseases into humans. But activists groups like the San Francisco AIDS Foundation say the experiment

was worthwhile. <p>



Communications director Derek Gordon says Getty is part of the tradition of activists helping push forward the search

for effective therapies, "We have to take some risks. 



<IMG SRC="getty_images/3.jpeg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120" WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



Risks have always been a very real part of the fight against HIV/AIDS and it's not a time for being timid and

inaction." <p>



As for Jeff Getty, he is planning another dose of radiation therapy early next year. And he says it's a treatment

that could help a lot more people, "All I know right now is that we stumbled on something that helped my clinical

health. I am a late-stage AIDS patient; I have very low T-cell count. Many would consider me to be near death, yet

I'm thriving following this therapy, and we are going to try it on other people." <p>



<b>The two doctors involved in the transplant, Dr. Steven Deeks and Dr. Suzanne Ildstad, were not available for

comment; they're preparing a paper for publication on the experiment. However, Dr. Deeks told the Oakland Tribune

some time ago that he attributes Getty's improvement to the radiation and he plans to do some follow-up research in

this area.</b><p>



<!------------------------------------------------->



</BLOCKQUOTE></td>



</tr>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<a href="../home.html"><img src="../../images/back.gif" width=82 height=36 border=0 vspace=2></a><br>



</td>



<td valign=top><center><a href="../../home.html"><img src="../../images/nc4_header_sm.gif" border=0 width=156

height=39></a><br><br>



