<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->



<TITLE> Strokes </TITLE>



<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif" LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973"

ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 



<br><br>



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150 height=1>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<blockquote>



<font size=+3><b>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title --------------------------->



Strokes 



<!-----------------------End Story Title --------------------------->



</b></font><br>



<font size=2><i>



Aired: 



<!-- Enter date aired -->



December 13, 1996



<!-------------------->



</i></font><p>



<!-----------------------Begin text --------------------------->



<b>Doctors who specialize in strokes say it's time to take a whole new approach to treatment. Currently, it's the

leading cause of disability in the United States and the third leading cause of death for adults. But if hospitals

start thinking "rapid response," experts say the numbers could be lowered.</b><p>



<IMG SRC="strokes_images/1.jpeg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120" WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



Getting to the hospital within minutes of a stroke can make all the difference. But doctors, too, will need to act

quickly; a big change from the way they've been thinking. <p>



"It was like, `We'll see the patient in a few hours or we'll see them tomorrow. Or give the patient an aspirin and

call me in the morning,' and that just doesn't make sense," says Duke University Medical Center's Dr. Mark Alberts.

<p>



For two days this week, the National Institute of Neurological Disorders and Strokes has been looking at solutions.

One solution is a drug called TPA. Already used for heart attacks, it can help stroke patients too, but only when

people take it within the first hours of noticing symptoms.<p>



<IMG SRC="strokes_images/2.jpeg" ALIGN=right HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120" WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



The other part of the solution is you and me. We need to know the warning signs so people can get to the hospital

quickly. That's where a new public service announcement comes in. <p>



<b>These new treatments would put strokes in the same emergency category as gunshot wounds and heart attacks.</b><p>



<!------------------------------------------------->



</BLOCKQUOTE></td>



</tr>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<a href="../home.html"><img src="../../images/back.gif" width=82 height=36 border=0 vspace=2></a><br>



</td>



<td valign=top><center><a href="../../home.html"><img src="../../images/nc4_header_sm.gif" border=0 width=156

height=39></a><br><br>



