<HTML>



<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->



<TITLE> Integrated Medicine</TITLE>



<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif" LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 



<br><br>



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150 height=1>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<blockquote>



<font size=+3><b>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title --------------------------->



Integrated Medicine



<!-----------------------End Story Title --------------------------->



</b></font><br>



<font size=2><i>



Aired: 



<!-- Enter date aired -->



December 9, 1996



<!-------------------->



</i></font><p>



<!-----------------------Begin text --------------------------->



<b>Studies show that around one third of Americans use alternative therapies to stay healthy. Until now many conventional doctors have frowned on it. But now, UC San Francisco is launching what could be a groundbreaking venture -- a task force to bring together both alternative and conventional therapies.</b><p>



"...There are a lot of things out there and it's important for us to understand what we know and what we don't know and try to figure out how to bring about new treatment," explains Dr. Laura Esserman, a member of the UC San Francisco Task Force on Integrative Medicine. <p> 



Dr. Esserman is also heading up a study on how alternative mind-body practices, such as yoga, meditation, and art therapy, can help women battling breast cancer. These will not replace conventional therapies, but be used in combination with them. Combination therapies are also being studied to see if diet and lifestyle changes can reverse heart disease and prostate cancer. <p>



"I think it is worth considering that what is seen as alternative medicine today is mainstream medicine tomorrow," says Dr. Andrew Weil. "That is just the history of how we proceed." <p>



Dr. Weil is a Harvard-trained physician, considered by many to be the guru of integrated medicine. He says while UCSF is the first big medical institution to take this approach, others are bound to follow. <p> 



"The conventional system no longer works economically, and at the same time there is this vast consumer movement to alternative medicine," adds Dr. Weil. "I don't think medical institutions have any choice but to move in this direction." <p>

 

Because UCSF is considered one of the top medical schools in the nation, experts say including integrative medicine in its curriculum could have a big impact on the next generation of doctors. "Change the focus a bit on how we train our students, teach our residents, teach ourselves, learn from each other, and learn from collaboration, and that's how we will learn and advance the field," says Dr. Esserman.<p> 



<b>The task force has only just begun its work. Right now it is still discussing exactly what alternative therapies it will focus on and how to combine them with conventional treatments.</b><p>



<!------------------------------------------------->



</BLOCKQUOTE></td>



</tr>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<a href="../home.html"><img src="../../images/back.gif" width=82 height=36 border=0 vspace=2></a><br>



</td>



<td valign=top><center><a href="../../home.html"><img src="../../images/nc4_header_sm.gif" border=0 width=156 height=39></a><br><br>



