<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->



<TITLE> Video Games & Epileptic Seizures </TITLE>



<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif" LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 



<br><br>



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150 height=1>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<blockquote>



<font size=+3><b>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title --------------------------->



Video Games & Epileptic Seizures 



<!-----------------------End Story Title --------------------------->



</b></font><br>



<font size=2><i>



Aired: 



<!-- Enter date aired -->



December 5, 1996



<!-------------------->



</i></font><p>



<!-----------------------Begin text --------------------------->



<b>Word that spending too much time playing video games could pose a serious health risk to some children. A new study, released today at the 50th annual meeting of the American Epilepsy Society in San Francisco, links the games to epileptic seizures.</b><p>



The new study by researchers in Italy and Britain says video games can create changes in brain wave patterns, triggering epileptic seizures in some children. Experts say this rare kind of epilepsy can also be triggered by other sensations such as music, reading, or even brushing one's teeth. <p>



The annual meeting of experts on epilepsy is discussing the latest ways of treating this and other more common forms of the condition; everything from diets high in fats that have shown to help suppress 

seizures in children to powerful new medications. <p>



"It's estimated that between 60% and 70% of people with epilepsy can have their seizures almost controlled, if not completely controlled, with available medications," says Dr. Marc Richter of the American Epilepsy Society. <p>



But the medications are not without side effects. When Beverly Cherry was a child, she had several seizures a day. Medications have helped reduce that to about one a month, but it has come with a toxic price. "I used to take tegratol for epilepsy and that controlled the seizures for two years," she says, "but it gave me aplastic anemia." She changed medications, but that triggered lupus and a series of other complications. <p>



Experts hope that in the next few years they'll have new, less toxic drugs and a greater understanding of what actually causes epilepsy. "If we can learn more about that process and learn more about how to intervene in it, we wouldn't be so worried about treating the seizures," says Dr. Richter. "We really would be more concerned about preventing the epilepsy." <p>



<b>The Epilepsy Society is also trying to break down some of the stigmatism and myths surrounding the condition, such as if someone is having a seizure, you should shove something in their mouth. They say that's the worst thing you can do. Instead, you should just leave the person alone until the seizure's over.</b>



<!------------------------------------------------->



</BLOCKQUOTE></td>



</tr>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<a href="../home.html"><img src="../../images/back.gif" width=82 height=36 border=0 vspace=2></a><br>



</td>



<td valign=top><center><a href="../../home.html"><img src="../../images/nc4_header_sm.gif" border=0 width=156 height=39></a><br><br>



<hr>



<font size=2>Copyright &copy; 1996 <a href="http://www.kron.com"><b>KRON-TV</b></a>. All rights reserved.</font>



</center>



</td>



