<HTML>



<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->



<TITLE> Birthday Revelations </TITLE>



<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif"

LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 



<br><br>



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150 height=1>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<blockquote>



<font size=+3><b>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title --------------------------->



Birthday Revelations 



<!-----------------------End Story Title --------------------------->



</b></font><br>



<font size=2><i>



Aired: 



<!-- Enter date aired -->



December 4, 1996



<!-------------------->



</i></font><p>



<!-----------------------Begin text --------------------------->



<b>Videos of a child's first birthday party is almost an American custom. But little

do parents know that those same videotapes might contain clues to whether a child may

be autistic. One doctor shows us the mannerisms to look for.</b><p>



<IMG SRC="birthday_images/1.jpeg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120"

WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



Karen Humphrey is a mother who has learned to take each day one step at a time.<p>



Her son Stephen, now eight, was diagnosed as autistic at age three. He crawled and

walked and played with his brother like a normal toddler. Then things changed. <p>



<IMG SRC="birthday_images/2.jpeg" ALIGN=right HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120"

WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



"The first indication to us that there was anything wrong was communication," says

Humphrey. "Not only the fact that he didn't develop language when you expected him to,

but non-verbal communication did not develop." <p>



Dr. Geraldine Dawson is an expert on autism. She uses home videos of first birthday

parties to diagnose children with the disorder, "We decided to focus on first birthday

parties because then we know exactly what age the child is at the time of the video,

and also because there are certain things that happen in a kind of standard way at

birthday parties." <p>



<IMG SRC="birthday_images/3.jpeg" ALIGN=left HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120"

WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



Case in point is Stephen's first birthday. Dr. Dawson noted that as Stephen crawled

across the floor, he wouldn't acknowledge the people calling his name. "He is not

turning around and looking at them," she points out. "So he isn't orienting to his

name and isn't making eye contact." <p>



A normally developing toddler is much more responsive. <p>



<b>This kind of early diagnosis of autism can make a big difference for the child.

Experts say it can improve a child's long-term prognosis.</b><p>



<!------------------------------------------------->



</BLOCKQUOTE></td>



</tr>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<a href="../home.html"><img src="../../images/back.gif" width=82 height=36 border=0

vspace=2></a><br>



</td>



<td valign=top><center><a href="../../home.html"><img

src="../../images/nc4_header_sm.gif" border=0 width=156 height=39></a><br><br>



<hr>



<font size=2>Copyright &copy; 1996 <a href="http://www.kron.com"><b>KRON-TV</b></a>.

All rights reserved.</font>



</center>



</td>



