<HTML>



<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->



<TITLE> Meth Abuse </TITLE>



<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif"

LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom>



<br><br>



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150 height=1>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<blockquote>



<font size=+3><b>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title --------------------------->



Meth Abuse



<!-----------------------End Story Title --------------------------->



</b></font><br>



<font size=2><i>



Aired:



<!-- Enter date aired -->



December 3, 1996



<!-------------------->



</i></font><p>



<!-----------------------Begin text --------------------------->



<b>The recent drug raid and arrest of a grade school teacher in Antioch

highlights what experts says is a growing problem in the United States: 

methamphetamine abuse. California is home to the most meth labs in the country.

On the Healthbeat, Pete Wilson looks at how the drug's reach extends to even the

most unlikely users.</b><p>



<IMG SRC="meth_images/1.jpeg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120"

WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



This girl, who does not want to be identified, was just fourteen years old when

she first tried methamphetamines. <p>



"The first time I used meth I was in 9th grade, and I liked it," she says. "It

kept me awake; I could do all my homework, you know. It was just kind of a good

feeling and I liked it. And I started using it more and more often." <p>



What began as experimentation quickly turned into addiction. <p>



A two-day conference in San Francisco on the rise in methamphetamine abuse says

that story is all too common. <p>



<IMG SRC="meth_images/2.jpeg" ALIGN=right HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120"

WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



In San Francisco alone, deaths linked to meth abuse rose 22 percent from 1993 to

1994. The number of meth-related hospital emergency room admissions rose 122

percent. <p>



And it's not just cities. Investigators think methamphetamines were involved in

the rape and murder of teenager Raina Bo Shirley in rural Potter Valley. <p>



"Methamphetamine is a tremendously addicting substance," states Dr. Alan Leshner.

<p>



Dr. Leshner is the director of the National Institute On Drug Abuse. He's worried

that the number of those trying methamphetamines will only increase because the

drugs are cheap and readily available. <p>



<IMG SRC="meth_images/3.jpeg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120"

WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



Dr. Leshner says long-term methamphetamine abuse leads to behavioral changes,

"What people call amphetamine or methamphetamine psychosis, such as delusions or

paranoia, that can be very long-lasting and very often irreversible." <p>



Drug counselors say it's an equal opportunity drug. "It doesn't matter how much

money you have, where you live, what color you are," says counselor Nora Carter.

"This disease can get you, too." <p>



<b>Experts at the National Institute On Drug Abuse say we need to improve

education efforts at both the state and local level to alert people to the

dangers of methamphetamines.</b><p>



<!------------------------------------------------->



</BLOCKQUOTE></td>



</tr>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



