<HTML>



<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->



<TITLE> Mammograms </TITLE>



<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif" LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 



<br><br>



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150 height=1>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<blockquote>



<font size=+3><b>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title --------------------------->



Mammograms 



<!-----------------------End Story Title --------------------------->



</b></font><br>



<font size=2><i>



Aired: 



<!-- Enter date aired -->



December 2, 1996



<!-------------------->



</i></font><p>



<!-----------------------Begin text --------------------------->



<b>Two new studies could help end a long running dispute over when a woman should start getting mammograms. The government's position is that fifty is the best age. But these new studies say that starting ten years earlier could save many women from breast cancer.</b><p>



Doctors say the earlier cancer is found, the better the chances of curing it, and that mammography can detect cancers too small to be felt. But some experts, including the National Cancer Institute, say using mammography on women under fifty does not improve their chances of surviving the disease. <p>



Two new studies from Sweden and Texas contradict that and support routine mammography for women at age 40. "The evidence today is really overwhelming," says Dr. Stephen Feig, Thomas Jefferson University. "The National Cancer Institute guidelines that were formulated back in 1993 are now obsolete and really need to be changed." <p>



The NCI says mammography is less reliable at revealing cancers in the dense breast tissue of younger women, leading to many false alarms. <p>



But most medical groups, including the American Cancer Society, are sticking to their guns and recommending women forty and over undergo mammography every one to two years. <p>



One new study shows that the incidence of small, potentially curable cancers is greatest in younger women; failing to diagnose them early could turn into a missed opportunity for a cure. <p>



<b>The dispute could be resolved as soon as next month. The National Institutes of Health is calling a meeting of scientists to examine all the available evidence on what is the best age for starting mammography.</b><p>



<!------------------------------------------------->



</BLOCKQUOTE></td>



</tr>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<a href="../home.html"><img src="../../images/back.gif" width=82 height=36 border=0 vspace=2></a><br>



</td>



<td valign=top><center><a href="../../home.html"><img src="../../images/nc4_header_sm.gif" border=0 width=156 height=39></a><br><br>



<hr>



<font size=2>Copyright &copy; 1996 <a href="http://www.kron.com"><b>KRON-TV</b></a>. All rights reserved.</font>



