<HTML>



<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->



<TITLE> Laser Tonsillectomy </TITLE>



<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif"

LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom>



<br><br>



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150 height=1>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<blockquote>



<font size=+3><b>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title --------------------------->



Laser Tonsillectomy



<!-----------------------End Story Title --------------------------->



</b></font><br>



<font size=2><i>



Aired:



<!-- Enter date aired -->



November 29, 1996



<!-------------------->



</i></font><p>



<!-----------------------Begin text --------------------------->



<b>For children, having their tonsils removed is no big deal. But for adults, it

is another matter entirely. Tonsillectomies for adults can leave them in intense

pain for up to a week after the operation. Now there is a new procedure that can

help cut that pain drastically.</b><p>



<IMG SRC="tonsilec_images/1.jpeg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120"

WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



Helen Garner is about to have her tonsils out. The tonsils are part of our bodies

immune system; meant to protect us from micro-organisms. But recently Helen's

tonsils have become less of a protection, and more of a problem. <p>



She describes the series of events that led to her tonsillectomy, "First I had

strep throat. And after that didn't go away, I got chronic tonsillitis. And so I

tried different antibiotics, but they never went away completely."<p>



But rather than undergoing conventional surgery to remove her tonsils, Helen is

undergoing laser surgery. There is no cutting involved.



<IMG SRC="tonsilec_images/2.jpeg" ALIGN=right HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120"

WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



Instead, the laser literally evaporates the tissue and, unlike traditional

tonsillectomies, this does not require general anesthetic; a local anesthetic is

all that's needed.<p>



California Pacific Medical Center's Dr. Dan Hartman says there's another big

advantage -- less pain.  "Probably the number one advantage is pain control," he

says. "You're looking at probably 10% to 15% of the typical pain you'd experience

with the tonsillectomy." <p>



The procedure is done on an out-patient basis, and takes only about half an hour.

Studies show it is as effective as a conventional tonsillectomy. "It allows you

to achieve the operation in the office," says Dr. Hartman. "And so for the

patient to avoid a general anesthetic and all the preparation that goes into

having an operation -- being admitted to the hospital and being discharged and

all that -- you're certainly saving them a lot of time and trouble." <p>



<b>The procedure costs around the same as a conventional tonsillectomy, but it's

not for everyone. Dr. Hartman says it is only really appropriate for adults, not

for children.</b><p>



<!------------------------------------------------->



</BLOCKQUOTE></td>



</tr>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<a href="../home.html"><img src="../../images/back.gif" width=82 height=36

border=0 vspace=2></a><br>



</td>



<td valign=top><center><a href="../../home.html"><img

