<HTML>



<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->



<TITLE> Roller Blading Danger </TITLE>



<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif" LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973"

ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 



<br><br>



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150 height=1>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<blockquote>



<font size=+3><b>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title --------------------------->



Roller Blading Danger 



<!-----------------------End Story Title --------------------------->



</b></font><br>



<font size=2><i>



Aired: 



<!-- Enter date aired -->



November 27, 1996



<!-------------------->



</i></font><p>



<!-----------------------Begin text --------------------------->



<b>A serious reminder that when it comes to in-line skating, you should use your head and protect your wrists and

elbows. A new study by the Centers For Disease Control And Prevention shows safety gear can dramatically reduce your

risk of in-line injury.</b><p>



<IMG SRC="blading_images/1.jpeg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120" WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



Some 22 million Americans used in-line skates last year. Almost 100,000 of them ended up in the hospital emergency

room with bad injuries; many because they failed to wear safety gear. <p>



At Skates On Haight in San Francisco, people who rent skates get free protective gear. But even then, many will not

wear it. "We had a lady that came in and rented some skates -- never done it before -- and she wouldn't wear the

pads," says J.J. Castro of Skates On Haight. "...When she came back, her knees and wrists and elbows were pretty torn

up." <p>



This latest study backs up just how valuable wrist guards and elbow pads are. The researchers found that in-line

skaters who wear wrist guards are ten times less likely than those who don't wear them to injure themselves. Those

who wear elbow pads are more than nine times less likely. <p>



<IMG SRC="blading_images/2.jpeg" ALIGN=right HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120" WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



Experts say the typical injury happens when an inexperienced skater falls with outstretched arms. Orthopedic surgeon

Dr. Peter Slabaugh says even a simple fall can cause a compound fracture, "A fracture obviously is a serious injury

and requires casting at least, and potentially even surgery, particularly in the age group where this occurs -- young

boys and girls who are still growing. And a fracture through a growth plate in the wrist area is obviously

potentially a more serious injury in a child than it is in an adult."<p>



<b>Experts say another important piece of safety gear for in-line skaters of all abilities is a helmet that can

protect you against cuts and scrapes and reduce the likelihood of serious head injury.</b>



<!------------------------------------------------->



</BLOCKQUOTE></td>



</tr>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<a href="../home.html"><img src="../../images/back.gif" width=82 height=36 border=0 vspace=2></a><br>



</td>



<td valign=top><center><a href="../../home.html"><img src="../../images/nc4_header_sm.gif" border=0 width=156

height=39></a><br><br>



<hr>



<font size=2>Copyright &copy; 1996 <a href="http://www.kron.com"><b>KRON-TV</b></a>. All rights reserved.</font>



