<HTML>



<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->



<TITLE> Heal Your HMO - Pt.1 </TITLE>



<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif"

LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 



<br><br>



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150 height=1>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<blockquote>



<font size=+3><b>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title --------------------------->



Heal Your HMO - Part 1



<!-----------------------End Story Title --------------------------->



</b></font><br>



<font size=2><i>



Aired: 



<!-- Enter date aired -->



November 25, 1996



<!-------------------->



</i></font><p>



<!-----------------------Begin text --------------------------->



<b>Nearly 1 in 3 people in Northern California get their health care from Kaiser

Permanente - the oldest and largest HMO in the country. So when Kaiser has a problem

-- even a small crack in its huge medical system -- a lot of people can be affected.

But a state report says that when it comes to fixing those cracks, Kaiser's system is

sometimes slow to respond. NewsCenter4 Healthbeat reporter Pam Moore

investigates.</b><p>



<IMG SRC="hmo1_images/1.jpeg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120" WIDTH="160"

BORDER=1>



When 74-year-old Margaret Utterback woke up with a sharp pain in her side one morning

last January, she had no idea there was a ticking time bomb in her abdomen. The main

artery from her heart to her lower body was weakening, ballooning out. If it

exploded, she would bleed to death. It's what doctors call an abdominal aortic

aneurysm.<p>



At first, Margaret thought maybe she had twisted her back. But she was worried enough

to call her doctor at the nearby Kaiser Permanente Medical Clinic in Hayward. <p> 



When she started calling Kaiser at 8:30 that morning, she didn't have chest pains,

severe bleeding; she didn't know she had an emergency. She couldn't get through to

her doctor, so she called her daughter, 

Barbara, to come sit with her. Then she tried the doctor again. <p>



<IMG SRC="hmo1_images/2.jpeg" ALIGN=right HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120"

WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



"She was told they didn't have anything to see her and to call back after three

o'clock and try to get an appointment with urgent care that evening," says Barbara.

"As the pain got worse, she decided that wasn't going to work so she tried again, and

she got transferred from department to department..." <p>



Barbara says her mother called 6 or 7 times that day, but never talked to a doctor or

a nurse. That's because her calls were going to operators with only basic medical

skills -- who screen patient calls. <p>



Operators are supposed to refer problem calls to a medical professional. <p>



"All we could get through to were clerical personnel," recalls Barbara. "There was no

medical advice person, there was no doctor, there was nobody with any medical

training that she could talk to -- who might have understood the symptoms and said,

'You need to be seen right away.'" <p>



<IMG SRC="hmo1_images/3.jpeg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120" WIDTH="160"

BORDER=1>



Finally someone gave Margaret Utterback an appointment with her doctor for 4:15. But

the pain was getting worse, so Barbara drove her mom to the clinic early (around

three o'clock). They explained the pain to the registration clerk and asked to see a

doctor as soon as possible. <p>



The clerk told them to take a seat. So Margaret sat in the waiting room squirming,

grimacing, her daughter says, for the next hour and forty minutes; pleading with the

clerk twice more for help. <p>



"And they did not send anybody out at any point to assess her," says Barbara.

"...Nobody."<p>



The doctor finally looked at Margaret shortly before 5 o'clock, and quickly found

that aneurysm. Still, it took another thirty minutes for an ambulance to take her to

emergency, where the bomb exploded.  

Margaret Utterback -- her heart pumping all her blood into her abdomen -- was rushed

to surgery.  She died two days later. <p>



<IMG SRC="hmo1_images/4.jpeg" ALIGN=right HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120"

WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



Dr. Gil Carroll did not handle Margaret Utterback's case, but is speaking for Kaiser.

"The office schedules are usually booked very, very tightly, and patients who require

immediate attention should not attempt to do this through the office," he says. "An

emergency of sort needs to be handled in the emergency room." <p>



Dr. Carroll says Kaiser did nothing wrong; that Margaret Utterback should have known

she was in trouble and gone straight to emergency. <p>



"So you're saying it's left up to her to assess her own medical condition?" <p>



"It was up to her to decide whether she had an emergency," replies Dr. Carroll. <p>



<IMG SRC="hmo1_images/5.jpeg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120" WIDTH="160"

BORDER=1>



"I don't think we can expect the patients to be their own doctors," remarks Dr.

Robert Derlet, Chief of Emergency at UC Davis Medical Center. <p>



Although Dr. Derlet declined to talk about the Kaiser medical system, he did react to

the story of Margaret Utterback's long day trying to get help. "That's just

unacceptable. I mean, somebody in severe pain, who's calling their medical group,

ought to be told in that first interaction on the phone that they need to go and be

seen by a physician right away," he says. "And to have difficulty in accessing a

system for eight hours, I mean, that's not a system." <p>



Kaiser says its system is working well for millions of patients, and that it's not

fair to judge the whole system based on the tragic death of one woman. <p>



But it IS fair to judge Kaiser on how closely it looks at a death like this for

possible cracks in its system. <p>



<IMG SRC="hmo1_images/6.jpeg" ALIGN=right HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120"

WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



Earlier this year, the California Department of Corporations, which oversees the HMO

industry, reviewed Kaiser's system and it found what the report calls "deficiencies"

in how Kaiser looks at bad results with individual cases for possible problems in

Kaiser's overall quality of care. <p>



In other words, when someone DOES fall through a crack in Kaiser's huge healthcare

system, Kaiser sometimes has trouble finding that crack. <p>



Kaiser doctors say they're working closely with the Department of Corporations to

correct any deficiencies. And state officials assured NewsCenter4 that none of

Kaiser's problems cited in the report 

is life-threatening. <p>



<IMG SRC="hmo1_images/7.jpeg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120" WIDTH="160"

BORDER=1>



The surviving family of Margaret Utterback hopes that statement proves to be true for

other Kaiser patients in the future. "Because I would not want anyone else to go

through what we are having to go through," says Margaret's granddaughter, Sherene.

"Cause not only did we lose somebody, but we lost somebody also knowing that she

could still be here if somebody had just listened." <p>



<b>Late last week, Kaiser said it reviewed records of the Utterback case and

discovered that one of its medical operators did tell Margaret Utterback to go to the

emergency room that morning. Utterback's daughter Barbara called that statement, "A

bunch of garbage."  Barbara says her mom was a Kaiser patient for fifty years, was a

very compliant patient, and would have done whatever she was told.</b><p>



<!------------------------------------------------->



</BLOCKQUOTE></td>



</tr>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<a href="../home.html"><img src="../../images/back.gif" width=82 height=36 border=0

vspace=2></a><br>



</td>



<td valign=top><center><a href="../../home.html"><img

src="../../images/nc4_header_sm.gif" border=0 width=156 height=39></a><br><br>



<hr>



<font size=2>Copyright &copy; 1996 <a href="http://www.kron.com"><b>KRON-TV</b></a>.

All rights reserved.</font>



</center>



</td>



</tr>



