<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->



<TITLE> Senior Depression </TITLE>



<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif" LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 



<br><br>



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150 height=1>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<blockquote>



<font size=+3><b>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title --------------------------->



Senior Depression 



<!-----------------------End Story Title --------------------------->



</b></font><br>



<font size=2><i>



Aired: 



<!-- Enter date aired -->



November 25, 1996



<!-------------------->



</i></font><p>



<!-----------------------Begin text --------------------------->



<b>For most people, the holidays are a time of fun and family. But for too many Americans, they can also be a depressing time. One group considered most at risk is seniors.</b><p>



For Karen Snow, the holiday season is tinged with sadness; full of memories of times past and of loved ones no longer here. "During the holidays your family has passed away or your husband. And, in my case, both," she says. "And you feel alone."<p>

                              

Karen is by no means alone. Experts say depression among the elderly is a major problem. And they are not the only ones at risk; it can strike anyone of any age. <p>



The warning signs are varied. They can include changes in appetite and weight, disturbed sleep, fatigue and loss of energy, feelings of worthlessness, even suicide. <p>



According to Dr. Thomas Brady, a psychiatrist with McCauley Behavioral Health Services, depression is treatable by medications and psychotherapy in 80% of  the cases. He says there are lots of ways to try and head off depression before it takes hold. <p>



First, try and keep the anxiety and stress surrounding the holidays to a minimum. "Lower your expectations; that's the first and foremost thing," he advises. "And, secondly, to moderate. We go overboard on gift giving, on gift receiving, on parties, on alcohol, on trying to cram it all in and have a great time. Well, it doesn't work that way." <p>



Karen Snow copes by staying busy volunteering for a seniors group. She says helping others helps her, "I helped a woman with a little thing. And when she was leaving, she said, 'God bless you my dear.' And you have no idea; that is so rewarding." <p>



<b>Experts say one of the biggest problems with depression is breaking down the stigma surrounding it. They say it's not a personal failing. It's a mental illness and should be treated like any other serious illness.</b><p>



<!------------------------------------------------->



</BLOCKQUOTE></td>



</tr>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<a href="../home.html"><img src="../../images/back.gif" width=82 height=36 border=0 vspace=2></a><br>



</td>



<td valign=top><center><a href="../../home.html"><img src="../../images/nc4_header_sm.gif" border=0 width=156 height=39></a><br><br>



