<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->



<TITLE> Insulin Pill </TITLE>



<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif"

LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom>



<br><br>



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150 height=1>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<blockquote>



<font size=+3><b>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title --------------------------->



Insulin Pill



<!-----------------------End Story Title --------------------------->



</b></font><br>



<font size=2><i>



Aired:



<!-- Enter date aired -->



November 20, 1996



<!-------------------->



</i></font><p>



<!-----------------------Begin text --------------------------->



<b>An estimated 400,000 Americans suffer from Type 1, or juvenile, diabetes.

That's where the disease completely destroys the body's ability to produce enough

insulin so the patient has to have insulin injections for the rest of their life.

Up till now there's been no way of preventing Type 1 diabetes, but a new study is

hoping to change that.</b><p>



Type 1 diabetes runs in Bryan Bariteau's family, so the 14-year-old is considered

at risk of developing the disease in the next few years. For that reason, Bryan

is taking part in a study to see if taking insulin capsules daily can prevent or

delay the onset of diabetes. <p>



Type 1 diabetes can happen at any age, and it's effects can be life threatening.

<p>



"The complications of  Type 1 diabetes include damage to the small vessels in the

eye, which can lead to blindness, damage to the small vessels in the kidney,

which can lead to kidney failure," says Stanford endocrinologist Dr. Darrell

Wilson. <p>



The researchers hope the insulin pills will work like an allergy shot; building

up the immune system of those at risk of diabetes and preventing the body from

destroying it's own insulin producing cells. If successful, it would be a big

breakthrough for people like Bryan. <p>



<b>Stanford is one of ten centers nationwide taking part in the study. They hope

to have the results in around 3 or 4 years.</b><p>



<!------------------------------------------------->



</BLOCKQUOTE></td>



</tr>



