<HTML>



<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->



<TITLE> New AIDS Drugs Denied To Children </TITLE>



<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif"

LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 



<br><br>



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150 height=1>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<blockquote>



<font size=+3><b>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title --------------------------->



New AIDS Drugs Denied To Children 



<!-----------------------End Story Title --------------------------->



</b></font><br>



<font size=2><i>



Aired: 



<!-- Enter date aired -->



November 18, 1996



<!-------------------->



</i></font><p>



<!-----------------------Begin text --------------------------->



<b>Over the past year a new class of drugs -- protease inhibitors -- have shown

remarkable promise in fighting the AIDS virus. But for the youngest victims of the

virus, the hope that those drugs offer is being denied. </b><p>



<IMG SRC="aidskids_images/1.jpeg" ALIGN=LEFT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120"

WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



Like a lot of nine-year-olds, Sam Fox is full of life and energy. But Sam is

different in one very important respect: he was born infected with the HIV virus.<p>



"It's heartbreaking," says Marilyn Fox, Sam's mother. "It's very real to him; the

fact that he may not live to be an adult." <p>



While new drug therapies using protease inhibitors are producing remarkable results

in adults, those drugs are not available to children. <p>



The reason is simple. The protease inhibitors have not been tested on children, so

doctors do not know how much of a drug or combination of drugs is safe for them. <p>



<IMG SRC="aidskids_images/2.jpeg" ALIGN=right HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120"

WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



"It's very difficult for [doctors], it's very difficult for the families of the

children," says Dr. Ann Petru, head of the Pediatric AIDS Clinic at Children's

Hospital in Oakland. "We're able to document over 

months, over years now, that children have rising amounts of virus and for those with

dramatic rises, we don't have drugs to treat them with." <p>



Since 1981, more than half a million adults have become infected with HIV. <p>



In contrast, there have been only around 7,200 children ages 12 and under who are

infected. Experts say that is too small a number to make it profitable enough for

drug companies to do the testing needed to make the drugs available for children. <p>

 

<IMG SRC="aidskids_images/3.jpeg" ALIGN=left HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 HEIGHT="120"

WIDTH="160" BORDER=1>



That's why parents like Marilyn Fox have begun a campaign demanding the FDA begin

drug safety studies in children right away. <p>



Sam has some demands of his own, too. <p>



"It's not fair for the other kids that don't have medicine," he says. "If us kids

don't get medicine, we won't survive. Please make it taste good, too." <p>



<b>For now, children like Sam are being given drugs that have been tested on

children; drugs like AZT and 3TC. But they have limited effectiveness. A lot of

doctors say it's only when kids get really sick and there is no option, that they are

willing to try the protease inhibitors on them.</b>



<!------------------------------------------------->



</BLOCKQUOTE></td>



</tr>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<a href="../home.html"><img src="../../images/back.gif" width=82 height=36 border=0

vspace=2></a><br>



</td>



<td valign=top><center><a href="../../home.html"><img

src="../../images/nc4_header_sm.gif" border=0 width=156 height=39></a><br><br>



