</h1>
</center>
<center>[ <a href="#followups">Follow Ups</a> ] [ <a href="#postfp">Post Followup</a> ] [ <a href="http://www.kron.com/nc4/talk_to_nc4/talk2nc4.html">Return to Talk to NC4</a> ]</center>
<hr><p>
Posted by <a href="mailto:WWALLACE@AOL.COM">WILLIAM WALLACE</a> on January 20, 1997 at 22:12:44:<p>
In Reply to: <a href="5226.html">Re: KAISER AND CARE-BEWARE!!!!!</a> posted by William Wallace on January 20, 1997 at 21:56:53:<p>
OREGON, CALIFORNIA MEASURES<br>WOULD REGULATE HMOS: STATE<br>BALLOTS<p>By By Tom Bemis<p>c.1996 Bloomberg Business News<p>Yucaipa, California, Oct. 30 (Bloomberg) - Linda Ross says she's voting for a California ballot<br>initiative to regulate health maintenance organizations because she believes her mother's 1991 death<br>at a Kaiser Permanente emergency room could have been prevented. <p>Kaiser Permanente was so concerned about holding down costs, she says, the health maintenance<br>organization refused to prescribe the drugs needed to treat her mother, Barbara Roberts. <p>Kaiser eventually paid a $150,000 arbitration award in the case, but denies that cost cutting was a<br>factor in Roberts' death, instead blaming human error. <p>The story, and others like it, are fueling voter backlash against health maintenance organizations in<br>California where two rival initiatives to regulate the managed care industry are on the ballot. <p>In Oregon an even more restrictive ballot measure would all but outlaw HMOs. <p>California health plans expect to spend at least $7.5 million fighting the measures. They've hired the<br>same Malibu public relations firm, Goddard-Claussen/First Tuesday, that came up with the Harry<br>and Louise television commercials the Health Insurance Association of America used in its<br>successful campaign to kill the Clinton administration's national health care plan. <p>Early polls show the California initiatives losing 2-1, although backers of one of the proposals say<br>their own polling shows 4-3 support for their measure. <p>Whatever the outcome of the elections, however, observers say resentment of HMOs and attempts<br>to regulate them are likely to grow as the managed care industry expands its coverage across the<br>nation. <p>``We will see this in other states, whether or not these pass,'' said Wanda Jones, president and<br>research director of New Century Healthcare Institute. <p>In California, two ballot initiatives, backed by different unions, are on the ballot. <p>Each of the two California initiatives would bar HMOs from restricting what treatments doctors can<br>recommend to patients, end bonuses paid to doctors who withhold care and require written<br>~%}standards for denial of care. <p>One measure, Proposition 216, backed by the California Nurses Association, would create a<br>consumer watchdog agency to monitor compliance with the new rules. The agency would be funded<br>with taxes on health company executives and HMO mergers. <p>The other proposal, Proposition 214, would use existing regulatory agencies to track compliance.<br>The measure, which could also be more easily modified by the state legislature, is supported by the<br>Service Employees International Union. <p>In Oregon Proposition 35 would outlaw capitation, the process by which HMOs collect set fees<br>from members and then provide service as needed to their subscribers. <p>The measure's author, Ophthalmologist Gordon Miller, says capitation is immoral and unethical<br>because it forces doctors to choose between serving their patients and making more money. <p>Opponents of the California ballot measures claim the plans would mean a return to double-digit<br>health cost inflation. <p>Both measures ``would add a lot of cost and bureaucracy,'' said Nancy Monk, a lobbyist for<br>PacifiCare Health Systems Inc. of Cypress, California. She said studies by HMOs show premiums<br>would rise 15 percent if either California measure passes. <p>PacifiCare has already contributed $311,000 to the campaign to defeat the ballot initiatives,<br>according to backers of Proposition 214. <p>Other big contributors include Kaiser, $785,000; Wellpoint Health Networks Inc. of Woodland<br>Hills, California, $550,000; and Health Systems International Inc., also of Woodland Hills,<br>$353,000. <p>Californians spend more than $100 billion a year on health care, according to a legislative report on<br>the initiatives. Almost 11 million residents are covered by managed-care plans. <p>Managed care helped hold the increase in nationwide health-care costs to an annual average of just<br>4 percent in the 1990s, compared with 11 percent in the 1980s, according to the legislative report. <p>Critics of the industry say managed care companies save money to giving doctors too many<br>incentives to withhold needed services. <p>``There's a conflict of interest between the doctors and the patients,'' said consumer activist Harvey<br>Rosenfield, author of Proposition 216. <p>Monk and other industry backers argue that giving doctors bonuses to control expenses helps drive<br>down health costs for everybody. <p>Passage of the ballot measures would ``make it very difficult for small businesses to provide health<br>care for their employees,'' said Allan Zaremberg, vice president of the California Chamber of<br>Commerce. <p>Critics also say the ballot measures are really designed to preserve jobs for unionized nurses. <p>``They promise patient protection, but they're really about job protection,'' said Janet Maira, a<br>spokeswoman for Taxpayers Against Higher Health Costs, the industry-funded group leading<br>opposition to the ballot initiatives. <p>Managed-care companies are also battling an initiative in Oregon that would return the state to the<br>old-fashioned fee-for-service method of coverage in which doctors are paid for services and<br>insurance serves as a backup. <p>Under an HMO ``a physician becomes the agent of the managed-care company or the insurance<br>company,'' said Miller. ``The patient is just a widget to make money off of,'' he said. <p>Opponents argue that the measure would undermine efforts to control costs. Because of HMOs and<br>other managed-care plans, only about 11 percent of Oregon residents are without health insurance,<br>said Kevin Earls of the Association of Oregon Industry. That compares with more than 30 percent<br>nationwide. <p>Whatever the outcome at the polls, supporters of the initiatives say pressure to reform the<br>managed-care industry is already growing. <p>They point to the recently passed federal law letting new mothers stay in the hospital for at least 48<br>hours after birth. In addition, hundreds of proposals are pending in state legislatures around the<br>country, according to Anderson. <p>Monk acknowledges the pressure but says new laws aren't necessary because competition will<br>force HMOs to be more responsive to customers. ``Reform is happening,'' she said. ``We have to<br>do that in order to be successful.'' <p>People like Linda Ross aren't buying, however. <p>``I stood by and watched my mother die, all the while believing they were going to do something,''<br>Ross said. ``It's time that we put some actual teeth in the laws that are supposed to protect us.''<br>10-30-96<br>1333EST<p>NYT-10-30-96 1333EST< 10-31 27 <br>
<br>
