<textarea wrap=on name="body" COLS=48 ROWS=10>
: OREGON, CALIFORNIA MEASURES
: WOULD REGULATE HMOS: STATE
: BALLOTS

: By By Tom Bemis

: c.1996 Bloomberg Business News

: Yucaipa, California, Oct. 30 (Bloomberg) - Linda Ross says she's voting for a California ballot
: initiative to regulate health maintenance organizations because she believes her mother's 1991 death
: at a Kaiser Permanente emergency room could have been prevented. 

: Kaiser Permanente was so concerned about holding down costs, she says, the health maintenance
: organization refused to prescribe the drugs needed to treat her mother, Barbara Roberts. 

: Kaiser eventually paid a $150,000 arbitration award in the case, but denies that cost cutting was a
: factor in Roberts' death, instead blaming human error. 

: The story, and others like it, are fueling voter backlash against health maintenance organizations in
: California where two rival initiatives to regulate the managed care industry are on the ballot. 

: In Oregon an even more restrictive ballot measure would all but outlaw HMOs. 

: California health plans expect to spend at least $7.5 million fighting the measures. They've hired the
: same Malibu public relations firm, Goddard-Claussen/First Tuesday, that came up with the Harry
: and Louise television commercials the Health Insurance Association of America used in its
: successful campaign to kill the Clinton administration's national health care plan. 

: Early polls show the California initiatives losing 2-1, although backers of one of the proposals say
: their own polling shows 4-3 support for their measure. 

: Whatever the outcome of the elections, however, observers say resentment of HMOs and attempts
: to regulate them are likely to grow as the managed care industry expands its coverage across the
: nation. 

: ``We will see this in other states, whether or not these pass,'' said Wanda Jones, president and
: research director of New Century Healthcare Institute. 

: In California, two ballot initiatives, backed by different unions, are on the ballot. 

: Each of the two California initiatives would bar HMOs from restricting what treatments doctors can
: recommend to patients, end bonuses paid to doctors who withhold care and require written
: ~%}standards for denial of care. 

: One measure, Proposition 216, backed by the California Nurses Association, would create a
: consumer watchdog agency to monitor compliance with the new rules. The agency would be funded
: with taxes on health company executives and HMO mergers. 

: The other proposal, Proposition 214, would use existing regulatory agencies to track compliance.
: The measure, which could also be more easily modified by the state legislature, is supported by the
: Service Employees International Union. 

: In Oregon Proposition 35 would outlaw capitation, the process by which HMOs collect set fees
: from members and then provide service as needed to their subscribers. 

: The measure's author, Ophthalmologist Gordon Miller, says capitation is immoral and unethical
: because it forces doctors to choose between serving their patients and making more money. 

: Opponents of the California ballot measures claim the plans would mean a return to double-digit
: health cost inflation. 

: Both measures ``would add a lot of cost and bureaucracy,'' said Nancy Monk, a lobbyist for
: PacifiCare Health Systems Inc. of Cypress, California. She said studies by HMOs show premiums
: would rise 15 percent if either California measure passes. 

: PacifiCare has already contributed $311,000 to the campaign to defeat the ballot initiatives,
: according to backers of Proposition 214. 

: Other big contributors include Kaiser, $785,000; Wellpoint Health Networks Inc. of Woodland
: Hills, California, $550,000; and Health Systems International Inc., also of Woodland Hills,
: $353,000. 

: Californians spend more than $100 billion a year on health care, according to a legislative report on
: the initiatives. Almost 11 million residents are covered by managed-care plans. 

: Managed care helped hold the increase in nationwide health-care costs to an annual average of just
: 4 percent in the 1990s, compared with 11 percent in the 1980s, according to the legislative report. 

: Critics of the industry say managed care companies save money to giving doctors too many
: incentives to withhold needed services. 

: ``There's a conflict of interest between the doctors and the patients,'' said consumer activist Harvey
: Rosenfield, author of Proposition 216. 

: Monk and other industry backers argue that giving doctors bonuses to control expenses helps drive
: down health costs for everybody. 

: Passage of the ballot measures would ``make it very difficult for small businesses to provide health
: care for their employees,'' said Allan Zaremberg, vice president of the California Chamber of
: Commerce. 

: Critics also say the ballot measures are really designed to preserve jobs for unionized nurses. 

: ``They promise patient protection, but they're really about job protection,'' said Janet Maira, a
: spokeswoman for Taxpayers Against Higher Health Costs, the industry-funded group leading
: opposition to the ballot initiatives. 

: Managed-care companies are also battling an initiative in Oregon that would return the state to the
: old-fashioned fee-for-service method of coverage in which doctors are paid for services and
: insurance serves as a backup. 

: Under an HMO ``a physician becomes the agent of the managed-care company or the insurance
: company,'' said Miller. ``The patient is just a widget to make money off of,'' he said. 

: Opponents argue that the measure would undermine efforts to control costs. Because of HMOs and
: other managed-care plans, only about 11 percent of Oregon residents are without health insurance,
: said Kevin Earls of the Association of Oregon Industry. That compares with more than 30 percent
: nationwide. 

: Whatever the outcome at the polls, supporters of the initiatives say pressure to reform the
: managed-care industry is already growing. 

: They point to the recently passed federal law letting new mothers stay in the hospital for at least 48
: hours after birth. In addition, hundreds of proposals are pending in state legislatures around the
: country, according to Anderson. 

: Monk acknowledges the pressure but says new laws aren't necessary because competition will
: force HMOs to be more responsive to customers. ``Reform is happening,'' she said. ``We have to
: do that in order to be successful.'' 

: People like Linda Ross aren't buying, however. 

: ``I stood by and watched my mother die, all the while believing they were going to do something,''
: Ross said. ``It's time that we put some actual teeth in the laws that are supposed to protect us.''
: 10-30-96
: 1333EST

: NYT-10-30-96 1333EST&lt; 10-31 27 

