http://kron.kron.com:80/nc4/people/davis.html 204.118.172.5 19970121210009 text/html 9067
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Communications/1.1
Date: Tuesday, 21-Jan-97 21:05:01 GMT
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>

<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->

<TITLE>NewsCenter 4 People: Belva Davis</TITLE>

<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->



</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif"

LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left  border=0>

<tr>

<td valign=top>



<img src="images/davis.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>

<img src="../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 



<br><br>



<br>

<img src="../images/greydot.gif" width=150  height=1>



</td>

<td valign=top>



<!-----------------------Begin Profile --------------------------->

<BLOCKQUOTE>

<FONT SIZE=+2><b>BELVA DAVIS</B></font><br>

<b>"California This Week" Co-Host<br>

"Bay Area Close-Up" Reporter for KRON's NewsCenter 4</b><p>



In an industry where the hours are long, the competition stiff and job security scarce, Belva Davis has prevailed as an esteemed broadcast journalist. Not only has she helped to shape today's television news, she has persisted as a revered social-political reporter and anchor for more than 25 years.<P>



Since becoming the first black female television reporter on the West Coast in 1966, Davis has been an inspiration for professional and aspiring journalists. She advocates community awareness through poignant reports, and demonstrates her involvement by being a board member for community organizations, a labor activist and a supporter of African-American culture. <P>



In her "Bay Area Close-Up" reports on NewsCenter 4, Davis profiles local people, organizations and institutions who are making a positive impact on their communities. On Sunday mornings, she joins Political Analyst Rollin Post as co-host "California This Week," KRON's weekly news and public affairs program covering topics such as political issues, fiscal concerns and city planning visions. <P>



After graduating from Berkeley High School, Davis worked at the Naval Supply Center in Oakland. Financially unable to attend college, she read voraciously on her own and began writing short stories. At 22, she quit the Navy to freelance as a writer for Jet magazine. It wasn't long before she signed on with several black newspapers in the region, including the Bay Area Independent and the San Francisco Sun-Reporter. <P>



Although Davis' concentration at the Independent was on the black social and political scene, she did just about everything, including "interpreting" for Malcolm X, who refused to talk to most white people, and when he would demand coverage of Black Muslim events, it was Davis who had to stand between him and Darrell Lewis, the white editor, and repeat what each said to the other. <P>



Davis began her broadcasting experience in radio. Her first position was with KSAN, a black station at the time, where she read clips from the newspaper. She moved over from KSAN to KDIA, KJAZ and then KNEW. While at KDIA, she worked in an office job in exchange for an air-shift. With the support of two sponsorships, Davis played music, spoke with studio guests and gained her first experience at reporting political news. <P>



With pressure mounting from the Civil Rights movement, the media began looking for blacks to "cross over" into white audiences. She was hired by KNEW to host a weekend radio show. She was soon promoted to a personality position as "Miss KNEW." It was here that Davis worked with rising Bay Area broadcast personality, Van Amberg. <P>



In 1966, with the support of the NAACP and several leaders in the black community, Davis made her first attempt to enter the television industry. She applied for an on-air reporting position at KGO-TV, the ABC affiliate in San Francisco, but did not get the job. <P>



Later that same year, she approached KPIX-TV, San Francisco's CBS affiliate, for an anchor position. This time she got it. Davis was hired to replace Nancy Reynolds, who left for Sacramento to follow Ronald Reagan's governorship. She joined Ben Williams, the first black reporter in the Bay Area, who was hired six months earlier by KPIX. <P>



At KPIX, Davis hosted and was instrumental in creating "All Together Now." The show was one of the first prime-time public affairs programs in the country to focus on ethnic communities. <P>



In 1971, Davis was offered a job by CBS to become a network correspondent, but declined before she began. Despite the lure of the position, she remained in the Bay Area and maintained commitment to her family, community and journalistic roots. <P>



After ten years at KPIX, Davis moved to KQED, the PBS affiliate in San Francisco. She anchored "A Closer Look" and then "Evening Edition" from 1977 to 1981, which were successors to the station's famed "Newsroom." <P>



Davis joined KRON-TV in March 1981 as NewsCenter 4 anchor and urban affairs specialist.  She also became co-host of KRON's Sunday morning news and public affairs program, "California This Week," with veteran political reporter Rollin Post. <P>



"California This Week" (previously called "Weekend Extra") has endured for more than a decade with Davis and Post at the helm. The show began as a ninety-minute magazine show featuring studio interviews with political figures, cause spokespeople and celebrities, along with short documentaries. Currently the show is produced in a half-hour format with studio interviews of local and national figures. Explaining why she has fought for programs like "California This Week," Davis says, "I truly believe democracy cannot survive without solid information on how government operates. This is where my philosophy started, and this is where I stand on the issue today." <P>



Davis has covered many of the major stories of the past two decades in a personal way that provides insight into people who make the news. Her portfolio includes: two interviews with Fidel Castro and a documentary on Cuba, "Yankee Come Back" (won two local Emmys); interviews with five U.S. presidents; an interview with Black Panther member Huey P. Newton in Cuba while he was there in exile; and coverage of several famous demonstrations of the late '60s and early '70s. <P>



Memorable encounters include: Her meeting with Dr. Martin Luther King Jr; a 1968 helicopter ride she shared with presidential candidate Bobby Kennedy en route to a Northern California Indian reservation, just before his death. <P>



Davis has received several dozen awards for her journalism, including national recognition from the Corporation For Public Broadcasting, Ohio State University, San Francisco State University and the National Education Writers Association. The Northern California Chapter of National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences honored her in 1996 with the Governor's Award, their highest lifetime achievement. She also received a lifetime achievement award from Peralta Community College District. She has won six local Emmys, a Certificate of Excellence from the California Associated Press Television and Radio Association for "best live coverage," Media Alliance's highest award, the "Golden Gadfly," as well as being honored by Sigma Delta Chi for "Outstanding Achievement." <P>



In 1996, she received an honorary "Doctorate of Humane Letters" from Golden Gate University and an honorary "Doctorate of Public Service" from John F. Kennedy University. The Media Academy of Oakland commemorates Davis' achievements as well, with an annual journalism scholarship. She is an honorary member of Alpha Kappa Alpha, and has been a presenter at many national conferences, including the Congressional Black Caucus annual weekend. She was honored to host the first Goldman Awards, considered the Nobel Prize for environmental accomplishments. <P>



Davis is a nationally respected labor activist, a vice president of the American Federation of Television and Radio Artists, and is extremely active in the community. In 1991, she was appointed a Governor of the Commonwealth Club of California, is active with Women's Forum West and Links Inc., Metropolitan YMCA, Blue Shield of California, the Fine Arts Museum of San Francisco and the Black Filmmakers Hall of Fame. <P>



Davis and her husband, retired KTVU Cameraman William Moore, the first African American cameraman in the Bay Area, have two children, Darolyn and Steven.



</BLOCKQUOTE>

<!-----------------------End profile --------------------------->



</td>

</tr>

<tr>

<td valign=top>

<a href="home.html"><img src="../images/back.gif" width=82 height=36 border=0

vspace=2></a> <br>



</td>

<td valign=top><center><a href="../home.html"><img

