<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->
    <TITLE>NewsCenter 4 People: Marty Gonzalez
</TITLE>
<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->

</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif"
LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left  border=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top>

<img src="images/gonzalez.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>
<img src="../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 

<br><br>

<br>
<img src="../images/greydot.gif" width=150  height=1>

</td>
<td valign=top>



<!-----------------------Begin Profile --------------------------->
<Blockquote>
<Font Size=+2><b>MARTY GONZALEZ</b></font><br>
<b>Weekend Co-Anchor of "Daybreak"</b><p>




Marty Gonzalez joined KRON as weekend co-anchor of "NewsCenter 4 Daybreak"
in July 1996. In addition to his work at KRON, Gonzalez is also an assistant
professor in the Broadcast and Electronic Arts and Operations Department at
San Francisco State.<p>

Gonzalez comes to KRON from KOCU-TV, Oklahoma City University's educational
wireless cable station, where he has been station manager since March.
Prior, he worked as a general assignment reporter for KRON from January to
March 1996. From January 1988 to December 1995, he was East Bay Bureau Chief
for KGO-TV in San Francisco. Before that, he worked at KCRA-TV in Sacramento
as a general assignment reporter.<p>

As a reporter, Gonzalez has traveled to Central America to explore the
impact of anti-American sentiment during the early '80s; Vatican City in
Rome to profile Pope John Paul II; Houston and Florida to report on NASA;
Baja California to profile the migration of Gray Whales; Mexico City to
cover the 1985 earthquake; Los Angeles to report on the Northridge
earthquake and Rodney King Riots; and Alaska to profile the 25th anniversary
of statehood. From 1980 to 1987, he was producer and host of  KCRA's "De
Colores," a monthly public affairs show exploring Latino issues.<p>
                 
Gonzalez's reporting from the Oakland Cypress Structure during the '89 Loma
Prieta earthquake contributed to KGO's Peabody Award for coverage of the
quake. He has also received awards from the Society of  Professional
Journalists for his work, including a news series on medical conditions in
Russia called "Heart to Heart."<p>

He received his Bachelor of Arts Degree in Mass Communications at California
State University at Chico. In 1993, he received a Kiplinger Fellowship Award
and went on to earn a Master of Arts Degree in Journalism at Ohio State
University. <p>

</blockquote>
<!-----------------------End profile --------------------------->


