<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->
    <TITLE>NewsCenter4:People: Brian Hackney
</TITLE>
<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->

</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif"
LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left  border=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top>
<!--
<img src="images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0>
-->
<br>
<Img Src="images/hackney.jpeg" height=129 width=117 border=0>

<img src="../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 

<br><br>
<br>
<img src="../images/greydot.gif" width=150  height=1>


</td>
<td valign=top>



<!-----------------------Begin Profile --------------------------->
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4><!---- Menu ------------------------><BR>
</H4>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H2>BRIAN HACKNEY<BR>
WEATHER ANCHOR AND SCIENCE REPORTER</H2>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4></H4>
Emmy-award winning Brian Hackney joined KRON-TV in December 1995 as weather
anchor and science reporter. In addition to providing weather reports weekdays
on &quot;Daybreak&quot; at 6:00 a.m., he also provides science reports for
NewsCenter 4.<BR>
<BR>
Hackney joined KRON from KGO-TV, the ABC affiliate in San Francisco, where
he was weather anchor on &quot;Channel 7 News at 11 p.m.&quot; In addition,
he was a member of KGO's &quot;Naturalists,&quot; the station's full-time
environmental reporting unit established in 1989.<BR>
<BR>
Beginning in October 1995, Hackney became co-host of &quot;Newton's Apple,&quot;
the Peabody award-winning educational science program on PBS. He received
an Emmy in 1992 for anchoring and writing a 30-minute environmental report
on earthquake hazards in California.<BR>
<BR>
Prior to KGO, Hackney was the science editor and weekday weather forecaster
for KNSD-TV (formerly KCST-TV), the NBC affiliate in San Diego. He won two
Emmys for science reporting and two Golden Mike awards from the Radio and
Television News Association of Southern California for &quot;Best Special
Segment&quot; in 1985 and &quot;Best Newscast&quot; in 1987. He also won
three San Diego Press Club Awards: two for his science and technology segments
and one for a feature story. <BR>
<BR>
Hackney graduated from California Polytechnic State University, San Luis
Obispo in 1982. He holds two Bachelor of Science degrees in physics and
electronic engineering. He served as Cal Poly's campus radio station program
director and also did voice-over work for the local NBC affiliate KSBY-TV.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-----------------------End profile --------------------------->


</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td valign=top>
<a href="home.html"><img src="../images/back.gif" width=82 height=36 border=0
vspace=2></a> <br>

</td>
