<HEAD>







<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->







<TITLE>NewsCenter 4 People: Catherine Heenan</TITLE>







<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->







</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif"



LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">







<table align=left  border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>







<img src="images/heenan.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 







<br><br>



<br>



<img src="../images/greydot.gif" width=150  height=1>







</td>



<td valign=top>



<!-----------------------Begin Profile --------------------------->



<BLOCKQUOTE>



<Font Size=+2><b>CATHERINE HEENAN</b></font><BR>



<b>Weekend Anchor and General Assignment Reporter</b><p>



Catherine Heenan was named weekend co-anchor in October 1988, after joining KRON's San Jose

NewsCenter as a general assignment reporter earlier that year. She anchors "NewsCenter 4 at 5" at

5:00 p.m. and "NewsCenter 4 Nightbeat" at 11:00 p.m. on Saturdays and Sundays. Her award-winning

"Nightbeat Extra" reports are currently featured weeknights on "NewsCenter 4 Nightbeat" at 11:00 p.m.

on Channel 4.<p>



Heenan, whose parents were born in Northern Ireland, grew up spending summers with family in Ireland

and England. She came to KRON from WTMJ-TV in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, where she worked as substitute

anchor and lead reporter. At WTMJ, she covered legal and political beats, and received numerous

awards for her investigative and general assignment reporting. Not only did her decision to leave

Milwaukee for San Francisco make headline news, she may be one of Milwaukee's only reporters to have

received a city proclamation naming a day in her honor. <p>



Heenan has received considerable recognition for her work, including a recent first place award from

the Radio and Television News Directors Association (RTNDA) and a local Emmy nomination for the

exclusive news series "Cloistered Nuns."  She and her photographer were the first and only outsiders

ever permitted to enter the monastery of the Poor Clares in Los Altos Hills.  Even parents of

cloistered nuns are not permitted inside.  In 1995, she anchored the newscast which won a local Emmy

for "Best Breaking News." <p>



She has won several awards each from UPI, RTNDA and the Milwaukee Press Club for her investigative

and documentary work and for breaking news. She was also named "Best TV Journalist" by Milwaukee

Magazine. <p>



Some of her most memorable reports while at KRON include the Northridge earthquake, the 1995 Super

Bowl and the U.S. troop deployment into Central America. <p>



Heenan holds a bachelor's degree in communications and journalism from Illinois State University. She

loves world travel, theater, books and movies. (Unless you seriously want to know -- don't ask her to

recite the names of movies by Alfred Hitchcock. She'll do it.)



</BLOCKQUOTE>



<!-----------------------End profile --------------------------->











</td>



</tr>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<a href="home.html"><img src="../images/back.gif" width=82 height=36 border=0



vspace=2></a> <br>







</td>



<td valign=top><center><a href="../home.html"><img



src="../images/nc4_header_sm.gif" border=0 width=156 height=39></a> <br><br>



