<HEAD>


<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->
    <TITLE>NewsCenter 4 People: Mark Jones
</TITLE>
<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->

</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif"
LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left  border=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top>

<img src="images/jones.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>
<img src="../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 

<br><br>

<br>
<img src="../images/greydot.gif" width=150  height=1>

</td>
<td valign=top>



<!-----------------------Begin Profile --------------------------->
<Blockquote>
<Font Size=+2><b>MARK JONES</b><Font><br>
<b>Newscenter 4 Contra Costa County Reporter</b><p>


Mark Jones joined KRON-TV as a NewsCenter 4 reporter in September 1986.  In
January 1994, he was named KRON's Contra Costa County reporter.<p>

Jones' broadcasting career began in the Midwest at WHB Radio in Kansas City, Mo.,
where he worked in news and commercial production from 1972 to 1975.  In April
1975, he went to KRGV-TV in Texas to be a news anchor, newswriter and daily radio
broadcaster.  In 1979, he moved to Orlando, Fla., station WDBO-TV to work as
field reporter, chief writer and co-anchor for their evening newscasts.  In 1981,
Jones headed to Connecticut to pursue television news consulting.<p>

The next year, Jones returned to news reporting at KPNX-TV in Phoenix, where he
was honored with four Rocky Mountain Emmy nominations and a first and second
place award for "Spot News" from the Associated Press.  In 1984, Jones returned
to Florida to work as a general assignmnet reporter at WTVJ-TV in Miami.  He won
two Emmy awards in 1985 for "Investigative Story" and "Spot News," as well as a
first place U.P.I. Regional Investigative Reporting award and the 1986 Ohio State
Achievement of Merit Award.<p>

Since coming to San Francisco, he has received 16 Emmy nominations from the
Northern California Chapter of the National Academy of Television Arts and
Science, bringing his career total to 23.  In 1992, Jones was nominated for his
investigative story "Dangerous Deliveries?"  In 1991, he won an Emmy award for
"News Talent," and was nominated for his feature "Children Who Have Never Seen
Rain," as well as for his work on the documentary "Romania's Secret Death Camps."
 In 1990, he won two Emmy awards:  best "Spot News" for his story "Child Death,"
and best "Scheduled News" for "Teen AIDS."  That same year, he won two other
nominations for "Manhunt" and "No Left Turn."  In 1989, he was nominated for
"Children of the Flames."  In 1988, Jones' work on "Pound of Flesh," "Conned by
Phone," "Movers from Hell," and "Power of Attorney," garnered four Emmy
nominations.  He also received two Emmy nominations in 1987 for the sports
reports "Sled Dogs" and "Renaissance Kid."  And in 1986, "Top of the Bridge" was
nominated for "Best Live Shot."<p>

Jones has also won the Thomas More Storke International Journalism award from the
World Affairs Council and two Best Documentary awards from the Hospital Council
of Northern California.<p>

A 1973 graduate of Missouri Western State, Jones earned a B.S. degree in Science
Technology and an A.S. degree in Criminal Law and Enforcement.  Active in
community affairs, he's hosted Easter Seal Telethons and was involved with public
affairs programs in Texas and Florida.  Jones loves all genres of music, and
enjoys bicycling, racquetball and cooking.<p>


</blockquote>


<!-----------------------End profile --------------------------->


</td>
</tr>
