<HEAD>


<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->
    <TITLE>NewsCenter 4 People: Vic Lee
</TITLE>
<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->

</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif"
LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left  border=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top>

<img src="images/lee.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>
<img src="../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 

<br><br>

<br>
<img src="../images/greydot.gif" width=150  height=1>

</td>
<td valign=top>



<!-----------------------Begin Profile --------------------------->
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE=+2><b>VIC LEE</b></font><br>
<b>General Assignment Reporter</b><p>

Vic Lee is a KRON-TV general assignment reporter with a specialty in Asian Affairs.  He has reported on victims of Japanese internment camps who fought for redress and reparations, he's covered the 1987 Coup d'Etat from the Philippines, and has made numerous trips to Japan on special assignment.<p>

"Duty Free Shoppers," Lee's investigation into the exploitation of Japanese tourists in San Francisco, revealed lease violations, discrimination, kick-backs, deceptive advertising and a potential multi-million dollar loss of rental revenue for San Francisco.  This prompted the San Francisco District Attorney, the State Attorney General's and the United States Justice Department's Organized Crime Task Force to pursue criminal investigations.  In turn, it resulted in a District Attorney settlement with Duty Free paying the largest civil fine in California history. <p>

Lee's reporting has earned local and national recognition.  He was honored with the prestigious George Polk Award of Journalism for "Best Local Reporting" for "Clean Rooms, Dirty Secrets," an investigative news series on hidden health hazards in Silicon Valley's semiconductor industry.  "Clean Rooms, Dirty Secrets" also received a "Best Investigative Reporting" award from The Associated Press. <p>

Lee has won Emmys for "Best Writing," "Best News Story," "Best Series," "Best Specialized Reporting," and "Best Multipart Feature."  Other awards include: UPI "Best Spot-News Story" from United Press International (UPI); "Best Live Coverage," "Best Investigative" and "Best Enterprise" from Associated Press (AP); "Best Television Enterprise Reporting" from the Society of Professional Journalists (SPJ); and "Best TV Reporting," "Unlimited Subject Matter" and "Asian Amerian Issues" national awards from the Asian American Journalists Association (AAJA). <p>

Lee also received much acclaim for "Airlift Africa and the Faces of Hunger," for which he spent one month in Sudan and Ethiopia.  The documentary garnered a UPI award, a CINE Golden Eagle award and a New York Film Festival gold award, all for "Best Documentary."  The series on the African famine also received an AP award for "Best Mini-Series." <p>

An internship at the New York Times influenced Lee to pursue a career in journalism.  After graduating from San Jose State University in 1969, Lee worked for United Press International in Tokyo, Portland and Los Angeles, where he was State Broadcast Editor. <p>

In 1972, Lee moved to San Francisco and has since worked at KRON as writer, assignment editor, news producer and managing editor, spending 1988-89 as the station's Asian Affairs Reporter in an effort to boost coverage of the Bay Area's fast growing Asian-American communities. <p>

Lee took a nine-month leave of absence in 1980 to continue Chinese studies through a grant from the Mandarin Language Institute in Taipai.  He also speaks Japanese, the language of his homeland.<p>


</BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-----------------------End profile --------------------------->


</td>
</tr>
