<HEAD>


<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->
    <TITLE>NewsCenter 4 People: Greg Lyon
</TITLE>
<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->

</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif"
LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left  border=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top>

<img src="images/lyon.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>
<img src="../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 

<br><br>

<br>
<img src="../images/greydot.gif" width=150  height=1>

</td>
<td valign=top>



<!-----------------------Begin Profile --------------------------->
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE=+2><b>GREG LYON</b></font><BR>
<b>General Assignment Reporter</b><p>


If he hadn't run out of money while living in Redding, Calif. in 1970, Greg Lyon might never have become a news reporter.  Before that, he attended a junior college in Traverse City, Michigan, for two years, lived in Guatemala for three years and finished his college education at the University of Michigan, where he majored in economics and Spanish.  To make ends meet after moving to Northern California, Lyon filled out an application to become a photographer at the Redding Record-Searchlight.  The newspaper hired him -- as an apprentice reporter.  There, according to Lyon, "I got my training on the job at a paper which was one of the finest in the state in its time, staffed by grizzled veterans of the San Francisco Examiner, Wall Street Journal and L.A. Times.  They were my journalism school."<p>

After three years at the Record-Searchlight, Lyon tried his hand at freelancing, based in Shasta County.  A year later, he became a reporter/news director at KQMS Radio in Redding.  In 1975, Lyon moved to Lantana, Fla., where he worked as a reporter for the National Enquirer.  Eleven months later, he moved back to Northen California, this time to become a newswriter/producer at KGO-TV, San Francisco's ABC owned-and-operated station.<p>

In 1977, he moved to KRON-TV.  Over the years at San Francisco's NBC affiliate, Lyon has been a newswriter, field producer, line producer, investigative reporter, general assignment reporter, special projects reporter/producer, business reporter and executive producer.<p>

Since coming to KRON, Lyon has won a number of broadcast journalism awards.  His news series "Children of the Tenderloin," depicting what it's like to grow up in a tough San Francisco neighborhood, garnered a 1984 Gold Award from the International Film and Television Festival of New York and a 1983 Radio and Television News Directors Award.  "Marco Cordova," a sensitive report on a young boy coping with devastating birth defects, received First Prize in the category of Feature Reporting from the 1984 United Press International Broadcast Awards.<p>

For his work on "The War Within," a documentary about a unique program for Vietnam veterans suffering from "post-traumatic stress syndrome," Lyon received a DuPont-Columbia Award, a First Place Robert F. Kennedy Award in television news, an Award of Special Merit from the Academy Awards and a CINE Golden Eagle.<p>

Other honors include ten regional Emmys, an Associated Press "Mark Twain" award for "Best Newswriting," five San Francisco University Broadcast Media Awards, a Golden Gate Award from the San Francisco International Film Festival, a 1983 Silver Award from the New York International Film and Television Festival, one Connie Award, and five Radio and Television News Directors Association Awards.<p>


</BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-----------------------End profile --------------------------->


</td>
</tr>
