<HEAD>


<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->
    <TITLE>NewsCenter 4 People:Anthony Moor
</TITLE>
<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->

</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif"
LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left  border=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top>

<img src="images/moor.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>
<img src="../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 

<br><br>

<br>
<img src="../images/greydot.gif" width=150  height=1>

</td>
<td valign=top>



<!-----------------------Begin Profile --------------------------->
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE=+2><b>ANTHONY MOOR</b></font><br>
<b>General Assignment Reporter</b><p>

<P>Anthony Moor has gained a reputation in the Bay Area for intelligent,
critical reporting in the best traditions of journalism.</P>

<P>He joined the station as a general assignment reporter just two weeks
prior to the 1989 San Francisco earthquake, and spent the first night reporting
from the collapsed 880 freeway.</P>

<P>Viewers remember him for hailing then-Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev
into a sidewalk news conference in 1990. From uncovering waste and cronyism
at the Golden Gate Bridge District, to discovering an elected official
who drove agency automobiles on a license which had expired 15 years earlier,
Moor often scoops Bay Area print and television journalists on stories
of local interest.</P>

<P>NewsCenter 4 also relies on Moor to respond to fast breaking stories.
He covered the federal building bombing in Oklahoma, a volcano in Hawaii
and the Gulf War buildup in Saudi Arabia.</P>

<P>Moor was an investigative and general assignment reporter from 1987
to 1989 at WKBW-TV in Buffalo. From 1985 to 1987, he was a state capitol
and Santa Fe reporter for KOB-TV in Albuquerque, New Mexico.</P>

<P>In college, he majored in astrophysics and American civilization, but
it was his extracurricular work in radio that brought him to journalism.
Hoping to garner a disc jockey slot his freshman year, Moor found himself
assigned to news and never turned back.</P>

<P>Moor's professional reporting career began in Japan. ABC News' Tokyo
bureau hired him straight from college to work as an evening assignment
editor from 1982 to 1983. At the same time, he became a morning and weekend
news anchor for JCTV, Tokyo's only English language TV station. He also
filled in briefly as a freelance reporter for CNN.</P>

<P>From 1984 to 1985, Moor took a break from news, &quot;bought a one-way
ticket to Hong Kong,&quot; and traveled through Asia and Europe. Eventually,
he landed a job as master of ceremonies for Club Med resorts in Switzerland
and the Bahamas.</P>

<P>Moor is a three time Emmy nominee. Most recently he won the Northern
California Society of Professional Journalists Mark of Excellence award
for &quot;Broadcast News Writing.&quot; He has won a California School
Boards Foundation 1990 Media Award for &quot;Best Feature Story&quot; for
his series &quot;Beyond the 3R's,&quot; which explored the value of education
and traditional studies. While at WKBW in Buffalo, Moor won a regional
Associated Press (AP) Award for &quot;Spot News Coverage.&quot; The AP
of Western New York also honored him for his investigative work.</P>

<P>Moor is married to a native San Franciscan and enjoys rollerblading,
skiing and tandem cycling. Born and raised in Chicago, he considers his
adopted city, San Francisco, to be &quot;like the tropics.&quot; Moor graduated
cum laude from Williams College, where he was elected to Phi Beta Kappa.
He speaks fluent French, intermediate Japanese and basic Chinese. He serves
on the Board of Directors of the Northern California Society of Professional
Journalists.</P>


</BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-----------------------End profile --------------------------->


</td>
</tr>
