<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->

<TITLE>NewsCenter 4 People: Pam Moore</TITLE>

<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->



</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif"

LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left  border=0>

<tr>

<td valign=top>



<img src="images/moore.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>

<img src="../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 



<br><br>



<br>

<img src="../images/greydot.gif" width=150  height=1>



</td>

<td valign=top>



<!-----------------------Begin Profile --------------------------->

<BLOCKQUOTE>

<FONT SIZE=+2><b>PAM MOORE</B></font><br>

<b>News Anchor/Healthbeat Reporter</b><p>



Pam Moore co-anchors "First 4 News" at 4:00 p.m., "NewsCenter 4 at 5" and "NewsCenter 4 Nightbeat" at 11:00 p.m. weekdays on KRON-TV, Channel 4. She also reports "Healthbeat" segments on "NewsCenter 4 at 5." <P>



Moore joined KRON in March 1991 as co-anchor and general assignment reporter on "NewsCenter 4 at 10 on KOFY."  She gained additional responsibilities in December 1991, when she was named co-anchor of KRON's "NewsCenter 4 at 11" on Channel 4. In 1993, Moore was assigned to report on medical issues for "Health Beat" segments on "NewsCenter 4 at 5." In 1994, she was named host of "Health Matters," a half-hour public health and awareness program. Moore was named 5:00 p.m. co-anchor in April 1994. <P>



Before joining KRON, Moore worked at WBZ-TV in Boston, where she co-anchored "Eyewitness News: The Noon Edition" and was a general assignment reporter for the 6:00 p.m. news since January 1986. Prior, she was a general assignment reporter at KCBS-TV in Los Angeles. <P>



Moore began her broadcasting career as a news reporter at WJLB Radio in Detroit.  She then moved to WSPD-TV in Toledo, Ohio, where she was weekend anchor/reporter. From WSPD, she moved to WHAS-TV  in Louisville before going to Dallas station KXAS-TV, where she was an anchor on the noon and 5:00 p.m. news. <P>



Moore was honored by the Bay Area Black Media Coalition with a Beverly Ann Johnson Media Award in 1994. She received the 1995 Distinguished Community Service Award from the YMCA of the East Bay and the 1996 Wiley Manuel Law Foundation Award for Outstanding Community Service. While at KCBS, she recieved the American Cancer Society Award for her news series "Closing in on Cancer" and was nominated for an Emmy Award for a news series on illiteracy. <P>



Moore has served as Vice President of the Black Journalist Association of Southern California, and in August 1987 was elected to a two-year term as Vice President for Broadcast of the National Association of Black Journalists. She is a member of the National Association of the Advancement of Colored People, and the Bay Area Black Journalists. In 1989, she was honored by the Big Sisters Association of Greater Boston, an association that she volunteered with in various cities for nearly ten years. Currently, she is a mentor for an Oakland Public School student in a program organized by the Oakland Rotary Club. <P>



A native of Detroit, Moore graduated from the University of Michigan, where she earned a degree in Radio/Television and Film. 



</BLOCKQUOTE>

<!-----------------------End profile --------------------------->



</td>

</tr>

