<HEAD>


<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->
    <TITLE>NewsCenter 4 People: Rollin Post
</TITLE>
<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->

</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif"
LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left  border=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top>

<img src="images/post.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>
<img src="../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 

<br><br>

<br>
<img src="../images/greydot.gif" width=150  height=1>

</td>
<td valign=top>



<!-----------------------Begin Profile --------------------------->
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE=+2><b>ROLLIN POST</b></font><br>
<b>Political Analyst<br>
"California This Week" Co-Host</b><p>


Rollin Post's goal as KRON-TV's political analyst is to give the audience a better knowledge of their elected officials and important political issues.  "I want viewers to understand what the politicians are doing, and why," Post says.<p>

In addition to his daily analysis for NewsCenter 4, he co-hosts KRON's Sunday morning public affairs program, "California This Week" with NewsCenter 4's San Francisco City Hall reporter, Belva Davis. During election times, Post is called upon for commentary for NewsCenter 4's Election Night Coverage.  He also hosts "Our World This Week," an international news show produced by BayTV (KRON's 24-hour news, sports and information cable channel) in cooperation with the World Affairs Council of Northern California.  "Our World This Week" addresses issues of international concern, emphasizing stories which affect the ethnically diverse communities of the Bay Area. <p>

In 1973, Post became the Bay Area television's first full-time political reporter.  A specialist in government and politics since 1964, he has covered fourteen national political conventions.  In 1978, he spent a week in Cuba reporting on trade, tourism and American hijackers living there.  He also covered the Philippine elections in 1986. <p>

Post joined KRON in September 1979.  Before that, he'd been with public television station at KQED since 1973, working on their news programs "A Closer Look" and "Newsroom."  He was also chief reporter and anchor on "California Tonight," a weekly PBS public affairs presentation seen statewide. <p>

From 1961 to 1973, Post was with KPIX-TV, San Francisco's CBS affiliate, where he concentrated on political and general assignment reporting. <p>

Early in his career, Post became head writer and producer for "The Paul Coates Report," a nationally-syndicated television interview show. He also served as a newswriter for CBS Radio in Hollywood. <p>

In April 1983, Post received the prestigious Broadcast Preceptor Award from the 32nd annual San Francisco State University Broadcast Industry Conference for his "Outstanding Contributions to the Industry."  One year later, he was one of three media figures honored by the Coro Foundation for their influential participation in the public arena.  In 1991, Post received the Outstanding Journalism Award from Sigma Delta Chi, the professional journalism fraternity. <p>

A graduate of the University of California at Berkeley, Post lives in Marin County with his wife Diane.  He has three children and three grandchildren. Post's father is a former assemblyman from New York, and his grandfather was a three-time Pulitzer Prize-winning political cartoonist for the New York World.<p> 


           
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-----------------------End profile --------------------------->


