<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->

    <TITLE>NewsCenter 4 People: Gary Radnich

</TITLE>

<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->



</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif"

LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">







<table align=left  border=0>

<tr>

<td valign=top>



<img src="images/radnich.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>

<img src="../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 



<br><br>

<br>

<img src="../images/greydot.gif" width=150  height=1>





</td>

<td valign=top>







<!-----------------------Begin Profile --------------------------->

<BLOCKQUOTE>

<!---- Menu

------------------------></BLOCKQUOTE>

<BLOCKQUOTE>

<Font Size=+2><b>GARY RADNICH</font></b><BR>

<b>Sports Director/Sports Anchor</b><p>



"The biggest name in Bay Area Broadcasting, sports or otherwise.&quot;<BR>

--Ann Killion, San Jose Mercury News<BR>

<BR>

Since joining KRON-TV in 1985, Gary Radnich's unique off-the-cuff style

has developed into the standard by which TV and radio sportscasts are often

judged. He has been honored three times by the Associated Press for &quot;The

Best Sportscast in California.&quot; And his weekday KNBR Radio show has

been top-rated since its 1992 debut.<BR>

<BR>

Along with his duties at KRON's &quot;NewsCenter 4 at 6&quot; and

&quot;NewsCenter

4 Nightbeat&quot; at 11:00 p.m., Radnich hosts &quot;Sports Final,&quot;

the Sunday night program where major names in Bay Area sports appear weekly.

His timely &quot;Sit Down! with Gary Radnich&quot; specials have become

a KRON staple, and an example of Radnich's and the station's commitment

to sports. He also appears on BayTV, KRON's 24-hour news, talk and information

cable channel, where he hosts a live one-hour sports roundtable every Friday

at 9:00 p.m. and has his KNBR &quot;Gary Radnich Show&quot; simulcast weekdays

from noon to 2:00 p.m. <BR>

<BR>

Before joining KRON, Radnich was sports director at WBNS television in Columbus,

Ohio, where he helped the station emerge as the highest-rated local newscast

in the country. He also called play-by-play for Buckeye football broadcasts

with legendary Ohio State coach Woody Hayes.<BR>

<BR>

Prior to working at WBNS, Radnich was sportscaster at KTXL-TV in Sacramento.

He got his start in broadcasting at Las Vegas station KVVU-TV before moving

back to the Bay Area to do Fresno State football and basketball play-by-play

with the Oakland A's Monty Moore for KMPH-TV. <BR>

<BR>

Radnich grew up in San Jose, California where he was an All-American in basketball at Branham High School. He continued his career at both Brigham Young and the

University of Nevada at Las Vegas.</BLOCKQUOTE>



