<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->
    <TITLE>NewsCenter 4 People: Steve Raleigh
</TITLE>
<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->

</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif"
LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left  border=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top>

<img src="images/raleigh.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>
<img src="../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 

<br><br>
<br>
<img src="../images/greydot.gif" width=150  height=1>


</td>
<td valign=top>



<!-----------------------Begin Profile --------------------------->
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<Font Size=+2><b>STEVE RALEIGH</b></Font><BR>
<b>Meteorologist</b><p>

Meteorologist Steve Raleigh is KRON-TV's weekday weather anchor on &quot;First
4 News&quot; at 4:00 p.m., &quot;NewsCenter 4 at 6&quot; and &quot;NewsCenter
4 Nightbeat&quot; at 11:00 p.m. on Channel 4. While working at KRON, he
has pioneered the nation's first instant weather information access with
California Weather Networks.<BR>
<BR>
Raleigh came to KRON in July 1990 from WCNC-TV in Charlotte, NC., where
he was weeknight weather anchor for two-and-a-half years. In 1989, he was
the lead forecaster during Hurricane Hugo. Raleigh's forecasting led to
an award for his outstanding work from the Federal Emergency Management
Agency (F.E.M.A.) He also earned a &quot;Best Weatherman&quot; award from
the hometown paper.<BR>
<BR>
Previously, Raleigh worked at WLWT-TV in Cincinnati as weekend weather anchor
and environmental reporter. During Raleigh's two years there, he was tapped
to establish and anchor a nightly report where he managed a small staff.<BR>
<BR>
Raleigh had moved to Cincinnati from Memphis, Tenn., where he began as weekend
weather anchor and was promoted to weekdays at WREG-TV. His first television
job was at WLBT-TV in Jackson, Miss. There, he worked with a tornado chasing
crew while maintaining weather and reporter duties. He was named &quot;Best
Small Market Weatherman&quot; by the Associated Press in 1983. Raleigh's
broadcasting experience also includes radio, where he worked as a news reporter,
announcer and host of public affairs shows.<BR>
<BR>
Raleigh has a bachelor of science degree in broadcast journalism from Boston
University. He majored in meteorology at the University of North Carolina
in Charlotte, N.C. His work led to the seal of approval from both the the
National Weather Association and the American Meteorological Society, which
selected him to be an educational mentor for Bay Area science teachers.
<BR>
<BR>
Raleigh stays busy working with a number of charities in the Bay Area. A
family man, he and his wife, Julie, have two sons and two daughters.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-----------------------End profile --------------------------->


