<HEAD>


<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->
    <TITLE>NewsCenter 4 People: Suzanne Shaw
</TITLE>
<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->

</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif"
LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left  border=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top>

<img src="images/shaw.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>
<img src="../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 

<br><br>

<br>
<img src="../images/greydot.gif" width=150  height=1>

</td>
<td valign=top>



<!-----------------------Begin Profile --------------------------->
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<Font Size=+2><b>SUZANNE SHAW</b></Font><BR>
<b>News Anchor and Business Beat Reporter and Host of "New Media News"</b><p>

Unlike many successful journalists whose careers fulfill a lifelong dream,
Suzanne Shaw never even thought about being a journalist until she was well
into her college studies. As a junior at Stanford University, a course called
&quot;How to Read a Newspaper&quot; by the prolific sociology professor
Sanford Dornbusch turned her around. It was an intensive study of what was
being said between-the-lines, and how reporters covered the same stories
with extraordinarily different perspectives. For Shaw, who had already switched
majors several times, the Dornbusch course prompted a final move into Stanford's
communications department. &quot;Suddenly, all my interests came together,&quot;
says Shaw. &quot;I had finally found a discipline that took in virtually
all my pursuits, from history to science and environmental law. I realized
the subject territory for reporters is limitless, and that remains the kind
of intellectual freedom I find addictive.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
A Northern California native, Shaw and her three brothers grew up in Monterey,
where she attended the Santa Catalina School for Girls for more than a decade.
Her academic pursuits then took her to Stanford University for the next
two years. The beginning of her junior year, she broadened her horizons
at the Sorbonne in Paris, and spent the second semester studying comparative
literature at Berkeley.<BR>
<BR>
Upon graduating from Stanford, Shaw began writing for several magazines
in Los Angeles. Her first television experience was reporting, writing,
shooting and film editing for sister stations KSBW/KSBY in Salinas and San
Luis Obispo. About the job, Shaw says, &quot;For two years I was my own
boss. I did my own shooting and editing and lugged around all the l6mm film
gear. I'd write the scripts while the film was in the soup. It was a real
education.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Shaw's hard work paid off when she moved from the KSBW/KSBY's four-person
newsroom to the country's fifth largest TV market in 1976. KTVU in Oakland
hired her to write and produce for their 10 o'clock news. In 1977, she was
hired by KGO-TV as a general assignment reporter and relief anchor. She
anchored their weekend newscasts from 1982 to 1984, then anchored weeknights
at 6 and 11 for the next four years.<BR>
<BR>
Shaw was an enterprising reporter for KGO, where she reported the secret
U.S. training of Costa Rican troops a month before the networks broke the
story. She also became the first Northern California reporter in ten years
to negotiate the entry of a television crew into Cuba for a series of special
reports.<BR>
<BR>
After leaving KGO, Suzanne married Bill Shaw, the owner of a sports marketing
company in San Francisco. In January 1989, she came to KRON to co-anchor
&quot;NewsCenter 4 at 11,&quot; and to report for the station. She moved
to &quot;NewsCenter 4 at 6&quot; in September 1990. In February 1992, she
began her weekly &quot;Who's Hiring&quot; segments surveying job opportunities
in the Bay Area on &quot;NewsCenter 4 at 6.&quot; In April 1994, Shaw took
on an additional newscast when she was named the co-anchor of &quot;NewsCenter
4 at 5.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
In 1995, she was named host of &quot;New Media News,&quot; a daily program
covering the most recent news on emerging technology with an emphasis on
computer users. Co-produced at KRON's San Jose NewsCenter in Sillicon Valley
by KRON Video Enterprises and Jones Computer Network, &quot;New Media News&quot;
airs nationally on JCN and sister channel Mind Extension University (ME/U).
The program also airs on BayTV, KRON's 24-hour news, talk and information
cable channel (Channel 35 on most Bay Area cable systems). <BR>
<BR>
In 1994, Suzanne and KRON Producer/Photographer/Editor Ken Swartz were honored
with a prestigious Alfred I. duPont-Columbia University Silver Baton for
their work on &quot;In the Shadow of the Wall,&quot; a documentary commemorating
the 10th anniversary for the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in Washington, D.C.
That same year, the Radio and Television News Directors Association (RTNDA)
named &quot;NewsCenter 4 at 6&quot; &quot;Best News Broadcast - 60 minutes,&quot;
which she co-anchors with Pete Wilson. In 1991, &quot;NewsCenter 4 at 6&quot;
was awarded an Emmy for &quot;Best Newscast.&quot; She also received a 1991
RTNDA Award for &quot;Best Special Program and Documentary,&quot; which
she shared with producer Ken Swartz and editor Jim Joy for their work on
&quot;Growing Up and Coming Out,&quot; a critically-acclaimed one-hour
documentary
on the toil, triumph and celebration of growing up gay.<BR>
<BR>
Shaw has been a Northern California television reporter and anchor since
1975. &quot;I enjoy the challenge of reporting and anchoring in such a
competitive
market,&quot; she says about working in the Bay Area. &quot;I'm thrilled
with KRON's progressive approach toward news and programming.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Her commitment to public service keeps her in close contact with the local
community. In addition to co-hosting KRON's &quot;For Those Who Care&quot;
and &quot;Easter Seals&quot; programs, Shaw is the honorary co-chairwoman
of the DANNY Foundation, local Child Abuse Councils and Oakes Children's
Center.<BR>
<BR>
In addition to the awards she has won while at KRON, her career has also
been marked by distinction, with Emmys from the Northern California Chapter
of the National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences for &quot;Best Coverage
of Breaking News by a Reporter,&quot; and a shared Emmy for &quot;Best Newscast
Production.&quot; In 1986, she was honored with the Eugene Block Journalism
Award for excellence in Public Affairs production for her segment on &quot;Day
Care Dilemma,&quot; and in 1987 she won the Radio and Television News Directors
Association Award for &quot;Best Newscast.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-----------------------End profile --------------------------->


</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td valign=top>
<a href="home.html"><img src="../images/back.gif" width=82 height=36 border=0
vspace=2></a> <br>

</td>
<td valign=top><center><a href="../home.html"><img
src="../images/nc4_header_sm.gif" border=0 width=156 height=39></a> <br><br>
