<HTML>
<HEAD>


<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->
    <TITLE>NewsCenter 4 People: Tom Sinkovitz
</TITLE>
<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->

</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif"
LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left  border=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top>

<img src="images/sinkovitz.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>
<img src="../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 

<br><br>

<br>
<img src="../images/greydot.gif" width=150  height=1>

</td>
<td valign=top>



<!-----------------------Begin Profile --------------------------->

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<Font Size=+2><b>TOM SINKOVITZ</b></font><BR>
<b>News Anchor and General Assignment Reporter</b><p>

Tom Sinkovitz is co-anchor of "First 4 News" at 4:00 p.m. and NewsCenter 4 Sunday evenings.  He is also a general assignment reporter.<P>
  
One of Tom Sinkovitz's most difficult experiences in broadcasting involved the near catastrophe at the Three Mile Island nuclear plant just outside his hometown of Harrisburg, Pa. Sinkovitz was then the anchorman of the most respected news department in the area.  People depended upon the news media for accurate information since government representatives and spokespersons for the nuclear  power company frequently offered conflicting viewpoints on the scope of the crisis and on the need to evacuate.  Beyond that challenge, Sinkovitz's own family lived within evacuation circles being drawn by emergency planners.  He remembers vividly the day he asked his mother and others close to him to leave the city for their own safety, and so that he could remain on the air without concern for their well-being if a mass evacuation order made his presence on the air a professional responsibility.<P>

Before joining KRON in January 1990 as weekend news anchor and general assignment reporter, Sinkovitz was the lead reporter at WXIA-TV in Atlanta from 1984 to 1989.  While at WXIA, he was also weekend anchor, general assignment reporter, and "Healthcast" anchor for two years.  From 1983 to 1984, Sinkovitz was with WBAL-TV in Baltimore as a general assignment reporter.  Before that, he was at Cincinnati's WCPO-TV from 1979 to 1983, where he produced and anchored "Noon News," co-anchored "Evening News," and did general assignment reporting.<P>

From 1974 to 1979, Sinkovitz was the anchor and producer of Harrisburg's WHP-TV's 6:00 p.m. and 11:00 p.m. newscasts.  He was the news director at WKBO Radio in Harrisburg, Pa. during the early '70s and served simultaneously as legislative correspondent for WPVI-TV in Philadelphia and what was then WIIC-TV in Pittsburgh, Pa.  From 1969 to 1970, Sinkovitz worked with the American Forces Vietnam Network in Saigon.  It was here where Sinkovitz faced another professional challenge.  In Vietnam, all military news reporters found it difficult to balance fair and accurate reporting with the U.S. Command's understandable efforts to use the military airwaves as what Sinkovitz calls "a propaganda tool."<P>

Sinkovitz has won three emmy awards for his news coverage over the years, two of them in San Francisco.  In 1995, he was recognized for his live coverage of an extraordinary shoot-out between police and a heavily armed gun fanatic.  He received another emmy award in 1991 for his very graphic look at the emergency room of a local hospital, and the impact of funding cuts on the poor who were served by the hospital.  His first emmy recognized his coverage of the explosion of the Space Shuttle Challenger in 1986, while he was working for WXIA-TV in Atlanta.  The major stories he has covered include the accident at Three Mile Island, the explosion of the Space Shuttle Challenger, Hurricane Hugo, the Oakland Hills Firestorm and the Los Angeles riots to name a few.<P>

Sinkovitz attended Wesley College in Dover, Del.  He enjoys all sports, particularly baseball, cycling, and golfing.  He jokes that his goal in life is to "turn fifty and get on the Senior Golf Tour."  Sinkovitz loves San Francisco because, as he says, "it is an international city," with many ethnic neighborhoods to explore.<P>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-----------------------End profile --------------------------->


</td>
</tr>
