<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->
    <TITLE>NewsCenter 4 People: Jan Wahl
</TITLE>
<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->

</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif"
LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left  border=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top>

<img src="images/wahl.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>
<img src="../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 

<br><br>

<br>
<img src="../images/greydot.gif" width=150  height=1>

</td>
<td valign=top>



<!-----------------------Begin Profile --------------------------->

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<Font Size=+2><b>JAN WAHL</b></font><BR>
<B>Film Critic</b><p>

<B>Host of Bay-TV's "Talkin' Pictures with Jan Wahl"</B><p>

Vancouver Magazine calls her &quot;San Francisco's sharp-witted solo answer
to Siskel and Ebert.&quot; Recognized as a woman of many hats, film critic
Jan Wahl joined KRON-TV's NewsCenter 4 in October 1991. Sporting a different
chapeau each week, she critiques recent movie releases, reviews new videos
and offers interesting background on the film industry. Her report air Fridays
on &quot;Daybreak&quot; at 6:00 a.m. and &quot;NewsCenter 4 at 5&quot; at
5:00 p.m., and Saturdays on &quot;NewsCenter 4&quot; at 8:00 a.m. on KRON,
Channel 4. Fridays at 7:00 a.m., she reports live on &quot;BayTV Morning&quot;
on BayTV, KRON's 24-hour news, talk and information cable channel. She also
is host of &quot;Talkin' Pictures with Jan Wahl,&quot; a live one-hour call-in
talk show covering movie and show business on Sundays at 9:00 p.m. on BayTV.<p>

In addition to her work at KRON and BayTV, Wahl provides cultural and show
business reports for KCBS Radio every Monday, Wednesday and Friday at 8:50
a.m. and 4:20 p.m.<p>

Before joining KCBS in December 1994, Wahl was the entertainment reporter
and movie/video reviewer at KNBR Radio, where she provided live reports
Monday and Friday mornings on the &quot;Frank &amp; Mike Show.&quot; She
also was the host of &quot;Hollywood Calling with Jan Wahl,&quot; a three-hour
weekly show which began in 1988. Prior, Wahl frequently appeared as a film
critic/historian on KGO Radio, and has been an entertainment columnist for
the San Francisco Independent since 1981. She also writes movie reviews
for the Marinscope Newspaper chain.<p>

Before coming to the Bay Area, Wahl worked for the ABC Network in Los Angeles,
first as a producer, and later as a stage manager and director of shows,
including &quot;Rona Barrett's Hollywood,&quot; &quot;The Lawrence Welk
Show,&quot; &quot;Match Game,&quot; &quot;Family Feud,&quot; &quot;Good
Morning, America&quot; and various specials such as the Oscar and Grammy
telecasts. In 1977, Wahl won an Emmy Award for producing and writing &quot;They
Still Say I Do,&quot; a humorous documentary on the palimony case of Lee
and Michelle Triola Marvin. That year she also became a member of the prestigious
Directors Guild of America.<p>

A movie enthusiast since her youth, Wahl began collecting movie memorabilia
at age seven. After moving to the Bay Area, she owned and operated Bridgeway
to Hollywood, a movie memorabilia shop in Sausalito. In 1987, she sold her
shop to pursue a media career. Wahl entered the journalism field as a newswriter
for KGO-TV, where she also produced two documentaries, while attending San
Francisco State University. During school, she also worked at KRON as a
panelist on a community affairs show called &quot;Youth Inquires.&quot;
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-----------------------End profile --------------------------->


</td>
</tr>
