<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->
    <TITLE>NewsCenter 4 People: Pete Wilson
</TITLE>
<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->

</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif"
LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left  border=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top>

<img src="images/wilson.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>
<img src="../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 

<br><br>
<br>
<img src="../images/greydot.gif" width=150  height=1>


</td>
<td valign=top>



<!-----------------------Begin Profile --------------------------->

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<Font Size=+2><b>PETE WILSON</b></Font><BR>
<b>News Anchor</b><p>

Pete Wilson co-anchors &quot;NewsCenter 4 at 6&quot; and &quot;NewsCenter
4 Nightbeat&quot;  at 11:00 p.m. weekdays on KRON-TV, Channel 4.  He  also
hosts  &quot;BayTV Prime&quot; Monday through Wednesday at 9:00 p.m. on
BayTV, KRON's 24-hour news, talk and information cable channel.<BR>
<BR>
He joined KRON in September 1990 as 6:00 p.m. anchor, adding the late newscast
in January 1991. <BR>
<BR>
Wilson is known for being one of the best informed news anchors in the area,
with a high level of journalistic skill and ability to communicate with
viewers.  He views himself as a writer, foremost, whose news style is to
make his delivery fit the words.<BR>
<BR>
He was a veteran San Francisco newsman when he arrived at KRON, after anchoring
at KGO-TV since 1983.  Before working in the Bay Area, he was a news anchor
at KTXL-TV in Sacramento for four years, where he helped build the newscast
from scratch.<BR>
<BR>
He began his broadcasting career at Milwaukee's WTMJ in 1971, writing and
reporting radio news, which led to television reporting for the NBC affiliate.
 He wore many hats while at WTMJ, including producing and hosting an early
morning TV show, anchoring a noon show, anchoring the 6:00 p.m. newscast
and hosting a half-hour prime-time talk show.<BR>
<BR>
Wilson has received a number of broadcast journalism awards, including five
Emmys from the Northern California chapter of the National Academy of Television
Arts and Sciences.  Two of these Emmys were in the category of &quot;Talk
Show/Special Programming,&quot; two for &quot;Feature&quot; and one for
&quot;Talent.&quot;  He has also won four Radio-Television News Director
Association awards for &quot;Best Newcast,&quot; &quot;Best Feature,&quot;
and &quot;Best Talk Show,&quot; a St. Francis Award for his documentary
series, &quot;Vietnam:  Gone, But Not Forgotten,&quot; and Associated Press
awards for &quot;Analysis&quot; and &quot;Feature.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Wilson volunteers extensively in the community through Project 90, an intensive
alcohol treatment group, the Mental Health Association, the National Association
of Visually Handicapped, the Child Abuse Council and Boys and Girls Clubs.<BR>
<BR>
A Wisconsin native, Wilson graduated from the University of Wisconsin with
bachelor of science and bachelor of arts degrees.  An avid film enthusiast,
he has a collection of over 3000 movies and dabbles in scriptwriting.  He
also loves the outdoors. </BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-----------------------End profile --------------------------->


</td>
</tr>
