<HTML>
<HEAD>


<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->
    <TITLE>NewsCenter 4 People: Linda Yee
</TITLE>
<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->

</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif"
LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left  border=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top>

<img src="images/yee.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>
<img src="../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 

<br><br>

<br>
<img src="../images/greydot.gif" width=150  height=1>

</td>
<td valign=top>



<!-----------------------Begin Profile --------------------------->
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE=+2><b>LINDA YEE</b></font><br>
<b>Reporter</b><p>

Linda Yee has been a general assignment reporter at KRON-TV since 1980.  She had previously worked at Channel 4 as a producer and newswriter from 1973 to 1977.  Between positions at KRON, Yee worked as a producer and writer, first for KGO-TV and then for CBS affiliate KPIX-TV.  Yee's journalism background also included newspaper reporting, having written for the Fremont Argus in 1973 and contributing articles to San Francisco's East/West Chinese American Journal from 1972 to 1977.<p>

Yee's extensive coverage of AIDS, beginning in 1981, resulted in many exclusive reports.  KRON-TV was one of the first stations to report the disease and continues to be a leading provider of up-to-the-minute facts.  In 1987, the World Affairs Council presented Yee with the Thomas M. Storke International Journalism Award for her story, "AIDS as an International Issue."  The Council again gave Yee a special award in 1988 for her story about a disfigured Taiwanese boy who came to the U.S. for treatment.  Yee also received recognition from the Alliance, a political action committee, for outstanding work in AIDS coverage.<p>

Linda Yee's reporting has garnered 11 Emmy nominations and four Emmy awards from the Northern California Chapter of the National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences.  In 1994, she received an Emmy for "Best Breaking Story" for the "Franklin Street Shootout," which involved NewsCenter 4 team coverage of a crazed gunman who fired off 100s of rounds at people and police, killing one officer.  She was awarded the "Best Breaking News Story" Emmy in 1990 for "Hostage," which covered an all night hostage situation involving more than 30 U.C. Berkeley students in a local bar/restaurant.  In 1989, she received the "Best News Story" Emmy awards for "Medical Missionaries," which covered homeless AIDS patients and the people who care for them. ("Medical Missionaries" also won the 1989 UPI First Place Award for "Best Serious Feature.")  She was honored in 1986 with the "Best News Story" Emmy for "Whose Baby?," a story about an adoption that went wrong.<p>				

In 1985, Yee was honored by UPI of the California-Nevada-Hawaii, with a second place award for "Best Feature," for her report "Project Last Chance," which examined a program for habitual juvenile delinquents.  The Northern California Radio-Television News Directors Association also recognized Yee with a "Best Reporting" award for "Whose Baby?" in 1986.<p>

Yee is a Bay Area native, with a bachelor of arts degree in journalism from San Francisco State University.<p>


</BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-----------------------End profile --------------------------->


</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td valign=top>
<a href="home.html"><img src="../images/back.gif" width=82 height=36 border=0
vspace=2></a> <br>

</td>
<td valign=top><center><a href="../home.html"><img
src="../images/nc4_header.gif" border=0 width=156 height=39></a> <br><br>
<hr>
<font size=2>Copyright &copy; 1996 <a
href="http://www.kron.com"><b>KRON-TV</b></a>. All rights reserved.</font>
</center>
</td>
