<HTML>
<HEAD>


<!-----------------------Begin Page Title --------------------------->
    <TITLE>NewsCenter 4 People: Emerald Yeh
</TITLE>
<!-----------------------End Page Title --------------------------->

</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../images/background.gif"
LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left  border=0>
<tr>
<td valign=top>

<img src="images/yeh.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>
<img src="../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 

<br><br>
<br>
<img src="../images/greydot.gif" width=150  height=1>


</td>
<td valign=top>



<!-----------------------Begin Profile --------------------------->
<Blockquote>
<Font Size=+2><b>EMERALD YEH</b><Font><BR>
<b>News Anchor<br>
Contact 4 Consumer Reporter</b><p>

Born in Princeton, N.J., Emerald Yeh grew up in Hong Kong, Tokyo and Macao,
before her family eventually settled in Honolulu.  She has also lived in
Georgia, Oregon and New York.  Reflecting on her worldwide travels, Yeh
says she feels most at home in San Francisco. <BR>
<BR>
In 1994, Yeh was name co-anchor of &quot;Midday&quot; and KRON's &quot;Contact
4&quot; Consumer Reporter.   Her &quot;Contact 4&quot; reports, which examine
consumer issues and provide viewers with problem-solving information, air
on &quot;NewCenter 4 at 5&quot; and &quot;NewsCenter 4 at 6,&quot;  Yeh
joined KRON in September 1984 as a weekend co-anchor, and was a general
assignment reporter during the week.  She began co-anchoring &quot;NewsCenter
4 at 5&quot; (then called &quot;Live at 5&quot;) with Evan White in August
1988.  In September 1990, she also became co-anchor of &quot;NewsCenter
4 at 11.&quot;  Yeh co-anchored both newscasts until December 1991, when
she gave up her 11:00 p.m. duties to focus on reporting human interest stories
dealing with social issues.  <BR>
<BR>
Yeh came to Channel 4 after a year-and-a-half of news anchoring at Cable
News Network (CNN) in Atlanta, Ga.  At CNN, she started out as an overnight
anchor, but within a month, was promoted to anchor &quot;Daybreak,&quot;
CNN's live three-hour early morning newscast.<BR>
<BR>
Before CNN, Yeh worked double duty as weeknight anchor and co-producer of
the news program at KPTV, an independent TV station, and anchor at KITV,
the ABC affiliate in Honolulu.<BR>
<BR>
Since joining KRON-TV, Yeh has won a number of broadcast journalism awards.
 She has received four Emmy awards from the Northern California Chapter
of the National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences.  In 1986, Yeh won
an Emmy for a report on &quot;Grandparents' Rights.&quot;  She received
another Emmy in 1987 for her sports story, &quot;Skipper Lynn,&quot; and
her third Emmy in 1989 for &quot;David Laird: Transplant Pioneer,&quot;
in the category of &quot;Best News Feature.&quot;  Yeh was awarded her fourth
Emmy in 1990, for the documentary program, &quot;Children of Courage.&quot;
 <BR>
<BR>
Yeh has also received three awards from RTNDA: &quot;Best Feature&quot;
in 1986 for &quot;Summer Camp:  Children of Alcoholics,&quot;  &quot;Best
Thirty-Minute Newscast&quot; in 1990 for &quot;NewsCenter 4 at 5&quot; and
&quot;Best Feature&quot; in 1993 for &quot;Holocaust Heroes.&quot;   <BR>
<BR>
In 1986, the Golden Gate Chapter of American Women in Radio and Television
honored Yeh for her outstanding achievements in broadcasting.  In 1987,
she was presented with a national UPI &quot;Best Feature&quot; award for
&quot;Summer Camp:  Children of Alcoholics.&quot;  In the same year, she
received the &quot;Distinguished Community Service&quot; award from the
Asian Business League of San Francisco for serving as &quot;a positive role
model to the younger generation.&quot;  In 1992, Yeh received the Asian
Pacific American award from the State Attorney General.  Yeh was also honored
by the American Psychiatric Association for her documentary, &quot;Kids
First: A Cry for Help&quot; in 1993.  <BR>
<BR>
In addition to all of her duties at KRON and her many achievements in and
out of the newsroom, Yeh still finds time to participate in many community
organizations.  She is a board member for the United Way and the Center
for the Pacific Rim.  Yeh served on a steering committee and is now a board
member for the new Asian Pacific American Fund.  <BR>
<BR>
A graduate of the University of Hawaii, Yeh majored in journalism and minored
in political science.  In 1980, she received a master's degree in journalism
from Columbia University. <BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-----------------------End profile --------------------------->


</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td valign=top>
