<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title--------------------------->



<TITLE> Country Sausage Soup</TITLE>



<!-----------------------End Page Title--------------------------->



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif" LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left  border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150  height=1>



<br><br>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<center><center><a href="http://www.excite.com"><img src="http://www.kron.com/sales/ads/excite_lessons6.2.gif" border=2 align=center alt="Lessons"></center></a>
</center></a>



<HR>



<blockquote>



<H1>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title--------------------------->



Country Sausage Soup



<!-----------------------End Story Title--------------------------->



</H1></blockquote> <blockquote>



<!-----------------------Begin Picture--------------------------->



<!-----------------------End Picture--------------------------->



<!-----------------------Begin Story--------------------------->



Courtesy of:<br>

Tante Marie's Cooking School<br>

271 Francisco Street<br>

San Francisco, CA  94133<br>

(415) 788-6699<p>



1  lb. Italian sausage<br>

1  lb. andouille sausage<br>

1/2  lb. hot Italian sausage<br>

1/4  cup olive oil<br>

1  large onion, chopped<br>

4  cloves garlic, minced<br>

1  tsp. minced jalapeno pepper (optional) <br>

4  carrots, peeled and chopped<br>

2  stalks celery, chopped<br>

1  green bell pepper, cut in half-inch dice<br>

1  red bell pepper, cut in half-inch dice<br>

1  medium rutabaga, peeled and diced<br>

4  red potatoes, diced and halved<br>

1/2 head Savoy cabbage, shredded<br>

1  28-oz. can Italian plum tomatoes, chopped coarsely<br>

1 1/2  qts. chicken stock and/or water<br>

1  tsp. freshly ground pepper<br>

2  tsp. salt<br>

2 tbs. minced fresh herbs such as oregano, chives, thyme<p>



Prick the sausages and cook in a skillet until browned and cooked through. <p>



In a large soup pot or Dutch oven, cook the onions in the olive oil until soft. Add the garlic and jalapeno and continue to cook for two more minutes.  Add the celery, carrots and bell peppers.  When partially softened, add the rutabaga, red potatoes, cabbage, tomatoes and stock.  Cover and cook for 30 

minutes. <p>



Cut the cooked sausage into one-inch pieces and add it to the soup with the ground pepper, salt and fresh herbs.  Continue to cook for another 10-15 minutes.  Taste and add salt and pepper to taste.  (Actually, this soup is designed to use up bits of uncooked vegetables such as broccoli stems or squash). <p>



Serves at least 20. <p>



<!-----------------------End Story --------------------------->



<B> <I>



<!-----------------------Begin Copyright--------------------------->





<!-----------------------End Copyright--------------------------->



</I></B>



</BLOCKQUOTE></td>



</tr>



