<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title--------------------------->



<TITLE> Victorian Toffee</TITLE>



<!-----------------------End Page Title--------------------------->



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif" LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left  border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150  height=1>



<br><br>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<center><center><a href="http://tours.excite.com/go.webx?128@@.ee6c02d/0"><img src="http://www.kron.com/sales/ads/excite_banned.gif" border=2 align=center alt="Banned Books"></center></a>
</center></a>



<HR>



<blockquote>



<H1>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title--------------------------->



Victorian Toffee



<!-----------------------End Story Title--------------------------->



</H1></blockquote> <blockquote>



<!-----------------------Begin Picture--------------------------->



<!-----------------------End Picture--------------------------->



<!-----------------------Begin Story--------------------------->



Courtesy of:<br>

Cathy Burgett<br>

Tante Marie's Cooking School<br>

271 Francisco Street<br>

San Francisco, CA 94133<br><br>



Ingredients: <br>

1  3/4-lb. sugar (scant 4 cups) <br>

water<br>

1 cup cream<br>

8 oz. butter (1 cup) <br>

12 oz. chocolate<br>

1 cup chopped walnuts<br><br>



Directions: <br>

Place the sugar in a medium large, heavy saucepan with enough water to make a paste. Place over low heat and melt the sugar, stirring occasionally. When the sugar is dissolved, turn up the heat and cook briskly until the mixture reaches a light caramel color. Add the cream and butter. Continue cooking, stirring constantly, until the mixture reaches the hard crack stage -- 295 degrees on a candy thermometer. Pour out onto a well-oiled, warmed sheet pan and spread evenly and slowly with a pastry spatula. Spread it about one-eighth inch thick. If the candy begins to harden before it can be spread evenly, place the sheet pan of candy in the oven for a few minutes to warm and soften. Allow the candy to harden at room temperature.<p>



Gently disengage the sheet of candy from the sheet pan. Spread the top of the toffee with a thin layer of melted dark chocolate and immediately sprinkle on the ground walnuts so that they stick to the chocolate while it is wet. Chill this, and then flip the sheet of toffee over onto another sheet pan and repeat the spreading of the chocolate and walnuts. Chill again briefly before breaking up. Store in a cool dry place, in a tin, or a non-porous plastic container.<p>



<!-----------------------End Story --------------------------->



<B> <I>



<!-----------------------Begin Copyright--------------------------->





<!-----------------------End Copyright--------------------------->



</I></B>



</BLOCKQUOTE></td>



</tr>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



