<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title--------------------------->



<TITLE> Prime Rib</TITLE>



<!-----------------------End Page Title--------------------------->



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif" LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left  border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150  height=1>



<br><br>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<center><center><a href="http://www.wellsfargo.com/special/skioffer"><img src="http://www.kron.com/sales/ads/wellsbanner.gif" border=2 align=center alt="Click Here If You Ski"></center></a>
</center></a>



<HR>



<blockquote>



<H1>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title--------------------------->



Prime Rib



<!-----------------------End Story Title--------------------------->



</H1></blockquote> <blockquote>



<!-----------------------Begin Picture--------------------------->



<!-----------------------End Picture--------------------------->



<!-----------------------Begin Story--------------------------->



(Recipe from Elaine Corn's book, "Now You're Cooking For Company")<p>



<b>Serving Sizes:</b><p>



3 Rib Roasts - Serves 6-8<br>

4 Rib Roasts - Serves 8-10<br>

7 Rib Roasts - Serves 14-20<p>



Ask the butcher to "cradle" the  roast; the bones are removed and tied back on so the roast gets the benefit of the bones' flavor. At carving time, simply cut the strings, remove the bones,  and carve the roast like a loaf of bread.<p>



<b>Directions:</b><p>



<b>1.</b> Take roast out of refrigerator for an hour. <p>

       

<b>2.</b> Preheat oven to 350 F. Place rack in oven's lower third. <p>



<b>3.</b>  Place meat -- bones down -- in a shallow roasting pan. Generously rub all fat with salt and pepper. <p>



<b>4.</b>  Roast 15 minutes per pound. <p>



<b>5.</b>  Get a temperature reading with an instant thermometer. Continue roasting until the meat reaches the doneness you like: <br>

Rare - 120 degrees<br>

Medium rare - 130 degrees<br>

Medium - 140 degrees<br>                                  

Beyond medium - I will not be party to this. <p>



<b>6.</b>  Remove roast from oven. Cover loosely with aluminum foil -- like a tent -- for 30 minutes. (Don't worry, it will stay hot.) <p>



<b>7.</b>  Cut strings, remove bones, then slice like a loaf of bread. <p>

                                                                               

<b>8.</b>  Pour juices into pitcher and serve with dinner. <p>



<!-----------------------End Story --------------------------->



<B> <I>



<!-----------------------Begin Copyright--------------------------->





<!-----------------------End Copyright--------------------------->



</I></B>



</BLOCKQUOTE></td>



</tr>



