<HEAD>



<!-----------------------Begin Page Title--------------------------->



<TITLE> Roast Turkey With Pan Gravy, Stuffing & Cranberry Chutney </TITLE>



<!-----------------------End Page Title--------------------------->



</HEAD>



<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="../../images/background.gif" LINK="#151bd4" VLINK="#496973" ALINK="#ff0707">



<table align=left  border=0>



<tr>



<td valign=top>



<img src="../images/header.jpeg" width=117 height=129 border=0><br>



<img src="../../images/nc4_grey.gif" width=111 height=24 align=bottom> 



<br>



<img src="../../images/greydot.gif" width=150  height=1>



<br><br>



</td>



<td valign=top>



<center><center><a href="http://www.kron.com/sales/wells"><img src="http://www.kron.com/sales/ads/ani3.gif" border=2 align=center alt="Wells Fargo Online Banking"></center></a>
</center></a>



<HR>



<blockquote>



<H2>



<!-----------------------Begin Story Title--------------------------->



Roast Turkey With Pan Gravy<br>

Chestnut and Sausage Stuffing<br>

Cranberry Chutney With California Figs<br>

Fresh Cranberry Sauce<br>



<!-----------------------End Story Title--------------------------->



</H1></blockquote> <blockquote>



<!-----------------------Begin Picture--------------------------->



<!-----------------------End Picture--------------------------->



<!-----------------------Begin Story--------------------------->



Courtesy of:<br>

Tante Marie's Cooking School<br>

271 Francisco Street<br>

San Francisco, CA  94133<br>

(415) 788-6699<p>



<b>Roast Turkey With Pan Gravy</b><p>



1  turkey<br>

salt and pepper<br>

butter, softened<br>

chicken stock or water<br>

1  stalk celery, chopped<br>

1  carrot, coarsely chopped<br>

1  onion, chopped<br>

2  sprigs parsley<br>

6  peppercorns<br>

flour<p>



Remove the wishbone from the turkey before cooking for easy carving.  Sprinkle the inside of the turkey with salt and pepper and stuff the turkey, if desired. <p>



Generally, one-half cup of dressing should be prepared for each pound of turkey (i.e. 5 cups dressing for a 10-pound turkey).  The dressing expands on cooking and therefore should be put in the cavity of the bird loosely.  Stuff the neck first.  Then pull the neck skin to the back, fold the ends of the skin 

under neatly and pin it to the back skin with skewers.  Turn the bird breast side up, lift each wing up and fold the tip under and press it against the back.  Now put the stuffing in the body cavity and close the opening by inserting 3 or 4 skewers through the skin over the opening and through the skin on the opposite side.  Then draw the edges together by crisscrossing a string around the skewers as in lacing shoes.  Tie the ends of the string together and fasten to the tailpiece. <p>



Place the turkey breast side up on a rack in a roasting pan.  Spread with softened butter (butter can be put under the skin if desired).  Cut three or four thickness' of cheesecloth large enough to cover the bird, and dip the cheesecloth in melted butter to coat.  Drape the cheesecloth over the breast of the turkey.  Place the turkey in a preheated 325 degree oven and roast approximately 15 to 20 minutes per pound.  Thirty minutes before the turkey is to be done, remove the cheesecloth.  Baste several times with the drippings in the pan.  If the turkey becomes too brown, cover it loosely with foil.While the turkey is roasting, prepare turkey stock by placing the turkey giblets, including the neck, heart and gizzards (not the liver) in a large saucepan with stock or water to cover by one inch.  Add the celery, carrot, onion, parsley, peppercorns and 1 tsp. salt.  Bring to a boil, skim and simmer gently 1 to 1 1/2 hours.  Strain and let cool.<p>



When the turkey is done, the leg joint will move easily, the flesh on the leg will be soft, and juices in the leg will run clear when pierced with a trussing needle.  When a meat thermometer is inserted about two-thirds way into the meat, the white meat should read 170 degrees and the legs and thighs 180 to 185 

degrees.  Remove the turkey from the pan and let rest 30 minutes.  Pour off most of the fat in the roasting pan, and add the turkey stock.  Bring this mixture to a boil, scraping up the brown particles on the sides of the pan.  Strain and measure the liquid.  For each cup of liquid, use 1 tbs. butter and 1 tbs. flour.  In a saucepan, melt the butter until bubbly.  Off the heat, sprinkle on the flour and cook until foamy.  Off the heat again, whisk in the turkey stock, bring again to a boil, whisking constantly.  Season with salt and 

pepper and serve in a sauceboat.  The chopped, tender giblets can be added to the sauce or the quickly sauted turkey liver chopped. <p>



Carve the turkey at the table by first removing the leg and thigh in one piece. Then, separate the leg from the thigh and slice the meat.  Then slice the breast meat in long thin slices from the top to bottom. <p>



<hr width=30%><br>



<b>Timetable for Roasting Turkeys</b><p>



10 lbs. - Unstuffed: 2 hours  Stuffed: 2 1/2 hours<p>



12 lbs. - Unstuffed: 2 1/2 hours  Stuffed: 3 hours<p>



14 lbs. - Unstuffed: 3 hours  Stuffed: 3 1/2 hours<p>



16 lbs. - Unstuffed: 3 1/2 hours  Stuffed: 4 hours<p>



18 lbs. - Unstuffed: 4 hours  Stuffed: 4 1/2 hours<p>



20 lbs. - Unstuffed: 4 1/2 hours  Stuffed: 5 hours<p>



22 lbs. - Unstuffed: 5 hours  Stuffed: 5 1/2 hours<p>



24 lbs. - Unstuffed: 5 1/2 hours  Stuffed: 6 hours<p>



<i>Remember:</i> A 20 lb. turkey needs to rest 30 minutes before carving. <p>



<hr width=30%><br>



<b>Chuck Williams' Chestnut and Sausage Stuffing</b><p>



1  lb. loaf french bread (with crust)<br>

1  medium onion, chopped<br>

2  ribs celery, chopped<br>

3  tbs. butter<br>

1/2  lb. fresh bulk pork sausage<br>

1  quart chicken stock<br>

1 1/2  lbs. fresh chestnuts, peeled, roasted, chopped OR one 20 1/2 ounce can unsweetened chestnuts<br>

parsley and thyme, chopped<br>

salt and pepper<p>



Tear the bread into small chunks. Spread on paper towels to dry overnight. <p>



Saut the onion in the butter until golden and set aside. In the same skillet, cook the sausage, stirring until finely crumbled and cooked through, about 10 minutes. Halfway through, add the celery. <p>



Soak the bread in as much chicken stock as it will absorb. Add the sausage mixture with the chestnuts.  Add the parsley, thyme, and salt and pepper to taste. Mix well. Put the dressing in a well buttered baking dish and bake at 375 degrees for 1 to 1 1/2 hours or until nicely browned. <p>



<hr width=30%><br>



<b>Julie Sahni's Cranberry Chutney With California Figs</b><p>



2  12-ounce packages cranberries<br>

2  oranges, chopped with skins, seeds removed<br>

1/2  cup chopped red onions<br>

4  tbs. fresh ginger, julienned<br>

2  sticks, cinnamon, 3-inches long, broken into halves<br>

1  tsp. salt<br>

3  cups sugar<br>

2  tsp. cayenne pepper<br>

2  tsp. mustard powder<br>

1/2  cup chopped walnuts or pistachios<br>

1/2  cup Black Mission figs, halved<br>

1/4  cup dark raisins<p>



Combine all the ingredients in an enamel pan and cook over moderate heat stirring often, until the sugar dissolves completely and the chutney comes to a boil. Continue cooking until the cranberries pop. Do not overcook or stir too much as the chutney will look unattractive. Store chutney in tightly sealed 

jars in the refrigerator. Keeps for six months.<p>



<hr width=30%><br>



<b>Fresh Cranberry Sauce</b><p>



1  3/4  cups water<br>

1  cup water<br>

1/4  cup orange juice<br>

4  cups cranberries, rinsed and picked over<br>

2  tsp. grated orange rind<p>



In an enamel saucepan, combine the sugar, water and orange juice.  Bring to a boil over a low heat and simmer 5 minutes.  Add the cranberries.  Cook the mixture over moderately high heat for about 5 minutes or until berries pop.  Stir in the orange rind.  Let the sauce cool then chill.  Makes one quart.<p>



<!-----------------------End Story --------------------------->



